const topics = [{"id": "topic1", "title": "Competences of the EU", "notesHtml": "\n  <div class=\"notes-block\">\n    <h3>Territorial Scope of EU Law</h3>\n\n    <div class=\"mini-card\">\n      <ol>\n        <li>EU law applies to any natural person who acts within the material scope of EU law. However, there is a difference in how EU law is applied to EU citizens and how EU law treats third country nationals acting in the material scope of EU law. EU citizenship depends on whether the person has the nationality of one of the Member States, in which case EU citizenship applies automatically, indicating that Member States have exclusive competences in relation to their nationality.</li>\n        <li>The EU is not a state, so it does not have its own territory. But it has the territorial scope of the reach of EU law, which is not exactly the same as the territories of the Member States. Some overseas parts of the territories of the Member States and some very distant islands, regarded as outermost regions, are excluded from the internal market and require adaptations of EU law.</li>\n      </ol>\n    </div>\n\n    <h3>Material Scope of EU Law</h3>\n\n    <p>Material scope of EU law deals with the competences of EU law, meaning how many competences have been transferred to the EU. There are three fundamental principles concerning EU competences: <span class=\"law-highlight\">principle of conferral</span>, <span class=\"law-highlight\">principle of subsidiarity</span>, and <span class=\"law-highlight\">principle of proportionality</span>. According to TEU Article 5(1), the principle of conferral deals with the limits of EU competences, while the principles of subsidiarity and proportionality deal with the use of EU competences.</p>\n\n    <h4>1. Principle of Conferral (limits of competences)</h4>\n\n    <p>According to TEU Article 5(2), under the principle of conferral the EU shall act only within the limits of competences conferred upon it by Member States in the Treaties to attain the objectives set out therein. This is the same as the principle of speciality. Moreover, paragraph 2 also says that competences that have not been conferred on the Union remain with the Member States, meaning that Member States retain residual competences.</p>\n\n    <p>Principle of conferral deals with explicit competences. However, international organisations can also have implicit competences. There is a “competence creep” seen in three developments indicating growing competences of the EU. Even though only the third development is called “implied power”, all three developments follow reasoning similar to implied powers:</p>\n\n    <div class=\"mini-card\">\n      <ol>\n        <li><strong>Effet utile</strong> — teleological or objective interpretation of EU competences, meaning that Union competences should be interpreted in a way so that the Union has sufficient competences to effectively attain Union objectives.</li>\n        <li><strong>Rise in EU’s general competences / flexibility clause</strong> — horizontal policies cut across policy fields. An example is the flexibility clause in TFEU Article 352(1). If it is necessary to achieve a Union objective, the Council can adopt measures even where the Treaty does not explicitly provide the power. The Council must act unanimously. This is the first limit to the flexibility clause.</li>\n        <li><strong>Implied power</strong> — if the EU has explicit internal power in a matter, then it also has implied parallel external power in that matter, meaning that it can make agreements with non-EU countries in that field.</li>\n      </ol>\n    </div>\n\n    <p>Further limits of the flexibility clause are also stated in TFEU Article 352. Paragraph 2 says that the flexibility clause should be in line with the principle of subsidiarity, meaning that the Union should take action only if the objective cannot be better achieved by the Member State. Paragraph 3 states that despite the flexibility clause, the EU cannot force harmonisation of Member States’ laws. Paragraph 4 says that the Council cannot adopt measures in the area of foreign and security policy.</p>\n\n    <h4>Legal Basis of EU Action</h4>\n\n    <p>Every act of the EU must have a legal basis. That is why the CJEU always checks whether the EU had sufficient legal basis and whether it can justify itself during the annulment procedure of any act of the EU or any secondary legislation.</p>\n\n    <p>To justify its actions, the EU has to specify:</p>\n    <div class=\"mini-card\">\n      <ol>\n        <li>whether it had enough competences in that field, meaning whether competences had been conferred to the EU by Member States under the principle of conferral,</li>\n        <li>whether the action was in line with Union objectives,</li>\n        <li>whether the correct type of act was used, such as regulation, directive, or decision,</li>\n        <li>whether the correct legislative procedure was followed.</li>\n      </ol>\n    </div>\n\n    <h4>Three Types of Competences</h4>\n\n    <p>There are three types of competences: exclusive competences, shared competences, and supporting competences.</p>\n\n    <div class=\"mini-card\">\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>Exclusive competences</strong> — according to TFEU Article 2(1), these are areas where only the Union can legislate and adopt legally binding decisions. However, Member States can also adopt legislation in these areas if they are empowered by the Union to do so. Exclusive competences are listed in TFEU Article 3.</li>\n        <li><strong>Shared competences</strong> — according to TFEU Article 2(2), these are areas where both the Union and Member States can adopt legislation. However, Member States can exercise their competences only to the extent that the Union has not done so, which implies that the Union takes precedence. At the same time, TEU Article 5(3) flips this around because, under subsidiarity, the Union can act in non-exclusive areas only if the objective cannot be sufficiently achieved by Member States and can be better achieved by the Union. Shared competences are listed in TFEU Article 4.</li>\n        <li><strong>Supporting competences</strong> — according to TFEU Article 2(5), these are areas where the EU can support, coordinate, and supplement the actions of Member States, but cannot adopt legislation harmonising national law. Supporting competences are listed in TFEU Articles 5 and 6.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n\n    <h4>2. Principle of Subsidiarity and 3. Principle of Proportionality</h4>\n\n    <p>These principles concern the <span class=\"law-highlight\">use of competences</span>, especially for shared competences.</p>\n\n    <p>According to TEU Article 5(3), the principle of subsidiarity suggests that the Union can adopt legislation in areas that do not fall within its exclusive competences only if the objective of the proposed action cannot be sufficiently achieved by the Member State, either at central, regional, or local level, but can rather, by reason of the scale and effects of the proposed action, be better achieved at the Union level.</p>\n\n    <p>According to TEU Article 5(4), the principle of proportionality suggests that the scope and content of EU actions should not exceed what is necessary to achieve the objective in the Treaty. The word “scope” refers to the type of act used: regulation or directive. A regulation directly affects the national legal system and is therefore less preferred by Member States. A directive offers more flexibility because states realise directives themselves within a limited amount of time, so directives are more preferred by Member States. That is why the Union may need to justify why it chose a regulation instead of a directive. The principle of proportionality was developed by the CJEU and is a general principle of EU law.</p>\n\n    <p>Both subsidiarity and proportionality are legal benchmarks for the lawfulness of actions adopted by EU institutions and are used as grounds of annulment of acts of EU institutions by the CJEU.</p>\n\n    <h3>The Scope of Application of EU Law</h3>\n\n    <p>Treaties are the reference points of the scope or field of application of EU law. This means that in order to figure out whether EU law applies in a specific situation, you need to refer to the Treaty and interpret it. There are two types of interpretation:</p>\n\n    <div class=\"mini-card\">\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>Broad interpretation</strong> — the scope of application of EU law is determined by powers or competences conferred on the Union, both explicit and implicit.</li>\n        <li><strong>Narrow interpretation</strong> — the scope of application of EU law is determined by the actual secondary legislation adopted by the EU, meaning specific directives and regulations, and not by the broader powers of the Union.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n\n    <p>The CJEU tends to adopt a broader interpretation as soon as the matter can have a potential effect on issues governed by EU law.</p>\n\n    <h3>EU as a Special International Organisation vs Member States</h3>\n\n    <p>What is special about the EU as an international organisation?</p>\n\n    <div class=\"mini-card\">\n      <ol>\n        <li>There is an unprecedented amount of transfer of sovereign powers, meaning competences, from states to EU institutions.</li>\n        <li>Because of this, EU institutions can adopt measures that are binding on Member States and on people operating within Member States.</li>\n        <li>The decision-making process of the EU is moving away from unanimity, meaning intergovernmentalism, and towards more majority voting, which is supranational in nature.</li>\n      </ol>\n    </div>\n\n    <p>Even though there has been a transfer of sovereign powers, states still want to guard their sovereignty as much as possible. This is visible in the principles concerning the division of competences between the EU and its Member States. This is especially seen in the principle of conferral, which states that the Union has only those competences that have been explicitly conferred on it by Member States. However, there is still competence creep, as seen in implied competences: effet utile, the flexibility clause, and implied powers or parallel external powers. This is also seen in subsidiarity in shared competence areas, which can give precedence to Member States rather than the Union, and in proportionality, which states that the scope and content of EU action should not exceed what is necessary to achieve the objective set out in the Treaties.</p>\n  </div>\n", "quizData": {"easy": [{"question": "Which statement best reflects the principle of conferral?", "options": ["The EU has inherent sovereign powers similar to states", "The EU may act in all areas not regulated by Member States", "The EU may act only within competences explicitly granted by the Treaties", "The EU may act whenever it is more efficient than Member States"], "correctAnswer": "The EU may act only within competences explicitly granted by the Treaties", "explanation": "Conferral = EU can act only within competences granted by the Treaties  A → EU is not sovereign B → opposite of conferral (this would be general competence) D → that’s subsidiarity logic"}, {"question": "What happens to competences not conferred to the EU?", "options": ["They fall under implied powers", "They remain with Member States", "They are governed by subsidiarity", "They are shared automatically"], "correctAnswer": "They remain with Member States", "explanation": "Residual competences remain with Member States  A → implied powers ≠ automatic fallback C → subsidiarity applies only once competence exists D → not automatic"}, {"question": "Which of the following best describes exclusive competence?", "options": ["Only the EU can legislate, unless it authorises Member States", "Both EU and Member States legislate simultaneously", "The EU can only coordinate actions", "Only Member States legislate unless EU intervenes"], "correctAnswer": "Only the EU can legislate, unless it authorises Member States", "explanation": "Exclusive competence = only EU legislates (MS only if authorised)  B → shared competences C → supporting competences D → incorrect structure"}, {"question": "Which principle governs the use (not limits) of competences?", "options": ["Supremacy", "Direct effect", "Conferral", "Subsidiarity and proportionality"], "correctAnswer": "Subsidiarity and proportionality", "explanation": "Subsidiarity + proportionality = use of competences  C → conferral = limits A/B → irrelevant principles"}, {"question": "Which statement about EU territory is correct?", "options": ["EU law applies only within EU institutions", "The EU has a fixed sovereign territory", "EU law applies exactly to Member State territories", "EU law has a territorial scope that differs from Member State territory"], "correctAnswer": "EU law has a territorial scope that differs from Member State territory", "explanation": "EU law applies within a distinct territorial scope, not identical to MS territory  B → EU has no sovereign territory C → oversimplification A → too narrow"}, {"question": "Which competence category allows the EU to support but not harmonise?", "options": ["Shared", "Supporting", "Exclusive", "Residual"], "correctAnswer": "Supporting", "explanation": "Supporting competences = no harmonisation allowed  A/C → legislative powers exist D → not a category"}, {"question": "EU citizenship is primarily based on:", "options": ["Economic activity", "Nationality of a Member State", "Residence in the EU", "Registration with EU institutions"], "correctAnswer": "Nationality of a Member State", "explanation": "EU citizenship = based on nationality of a Member State  C → residence alone insufficient A/D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Which is NOT a type of EU competence?", "options": ["Exclusive", "Supporting", "Coordinated", "Shared"], "correctAnswer": "Coordinated", "explanation": "“Coordinated” is not a Treaty category  A/B/D → all real categories"}, {"question": "Which principle ensures EU action does not exceed what is necessary?", "options": ["Conferral", "Proportionality", "Effectiveness", "Subsidiarity"], "correctAnswer": "Proportionality", "explanation": "Proportionality = EU must not exceed what is necessary  D → subsidiarity = “should EU act?” A → conferral = “can EU act?”"}, {"question": "Which institution typically checks whether the EU had a valid legal basis?", "options": ["Commission", "European Parliament", "European Council", "CJEU"], "correctAnswer": "CJEU", "explanation": "CJEU reviews legality + legal basis  A/B/C → political roles, not judicial review"}], "medium": [{"question": "Which scenario best reflects a breach of subsidiarity?", "options": ["EU acts where Member States could sufficiently achieve the objective", "EU acts in an exclusive competence area", "EU adopts a directive instead of a regulation", "EU acts with unanimous Council approval"], "correctAnswer": "EU acts where Member States could sufficiently achieve the objective", "explanation": "Subsidiarity breached if MS can sufficiently achieve objective  B → subsidiarity doesn’t apply to exclusive competences C → proportionality issue D → procedure ≠ subsidiarity"}, {"question": "Which of the following is a correct limit of Article 352 TFEU?", "options": ["It replaces subsidiarity", "It allows harmonisation in all fields", "It requires unanimity in the Council", "It applies to foreign and security policy"], "correctAnswer": "It requires unanimity in the Council", "explanation": "Article 352 requires unanimity  D → explicitly excluded (CFSP) B → cannot harmonise freely A → does not replace subsidiarity"}, {"question": "Which option best reflects effet utile?", "options": ["Narrow interpretation of EU powers", "Strict textual interpretation of competences", "Limitation of EU powers to explicit Treaty text", "Interpretation ensuring effectiveness of EU objectives"], "correctAnswer": "Interpretation ensuring effectiveness of EU objectives", "explanation": "Effet utile = interpretation ensuring effectiveness  A/B/C → all describe restrictive interpretation"}, {"question": "A Member State legislates in a shared competence area already regulated by the EU. What is the likely outcome?", "options": ["EU law becomes optional", "Both laws apply equally", "Member State may only act where EU has not exercised competence", "Member State law prevails"], "correctAnswer": "Member State may only act where EU has not exercised competence", "explanation": "MS act only where EU hasn’t exercised competence This is pre-emption logic  B/D → incorrect hierarchy A → EU law not optional"}, {"question": "Which situation best illustrates implied external powers?", "options": ["EU acts under subsidiarity", "EU delegates powers to Member States", "EU creates internal legislation", "EU concludes international agreements in an area of internal competence"], "correctAnswer": "EU concludes international agreements in an area of internal competence", "explanation": "Internal competence → external treaty-making power  C → internal only A/B → unrelated"}, {"question": "Which of the following best reflects the broad interpretation of EU law?", "options": ["Scope excludes implied powers", "Scope depends strictly on Treaty wording", "Only secondary legislation determines scope", "Scope includes potential effects on EU-regulated areas"], "correctAnswer": "Scope includes potential effects on EU-regulated areas", "explanation": "CJEU adopts broad interpretation where EU law may be affected  A/B/C → narrow approaches"}, {"question": "Why are directives often preferred over regulations under proportionality?", "options": ["They require unanimity", "They allow Member State flexibility", "They are legally weaker", "They avoid judicial review"], "correctAnswer": "They allow Member State flexibility", "explanation": "Directives = less intrusive → more proportionate  C → not about legal strength A → not required D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Which is NOT required for a valid legal basis?", "options": ["Action must pursue EU objectives", "Competence must be conferred", "Member State approval in all cases", "Correct legislative procedure"], "correctAnswer": "Member State approval in all cases", "explanation": "MS approval is NOT always required  A/B/D → all essential legal basis elements"}, {"question": "Which scenario best reflects competence creep?", "options": ["EU reduces its legislative scope", "EU expands powers through interpretation and flexibility mechanisms", "EU acts only within explicit Treaty powers", "Member States regain powers from the EU"], "correctAnswer": "EU expands powers through interpretation and flexibility mechanisms", "explanation": "Competence creep = expansion via: effet utile Article 352 implied powers  A/C/D → opposite scenarios"}, {"question": "Which statement best captures the tension in shared competences?", "options": ["EU always has priority", "Shared competences are purely symbolic", "Member States always have priority", "EU acts only when subsidiarity justifies it"], "correctAnswer": "EU acts only when subsidiarity justifies it", "explanation": "Subsidiarity = EU acts only when justified  A/B → too absolute C → ignores EU role"}], "hard": [{"question": "The EU adopts a measure under Article 352 TFEU without unanimity in the Council. What is the strongest legal argument?", "options": ["Measure is valid due to effectiveness", "Measure is invalid due to procedural defect", "Measure violates subsidiarity", "Measure is valid if Parliament approves"], "correctAnswer": "Measure is invalid due to procedural defect", "explanation": "Lack of unanimity = procedural illegality → annulment  A → effectiveness cannot override procedure C → subsidiarity irrelevant here D → Parliament approval insufficient"}, {"question": "A policy is not explicitly covered by the Treaties but is necessary for achieving EU objectives. Which is MOST accurate?", "options": ["EU must amend the Treaties", "EU may act under Article 352 TFEU, subject to limits", "EU cannot act", "EU may act only via implied external powers"], "correctAnswer": "EU may act under Article 352 TFEU, subject to limits", "explanation": "Article 352 allows action if: necessary within objectives limits respected  C → too restrictive D → unnecessary A → wrong"}, {"question": "Which scenario would most likely lead to annulment under proportionality?", "options": ["EU uses Article 352", "EU adopts overly intrusive regulation where directive suffices", "EU fails to act", "EU acts in exclusive competence"], "correctAnswer": "EU adopts overly intrusive regulation where directive suffices", "explanation": "Regulation instead of directive = disproportionate measure Key idea: least restrictive means  A/D → irrelevant C → no violation"}, {"question": "Which statement best reflects the real limitation of conferral in practice?", "options": ["It applies only to shared competences", "It strictly prevents EU expansion", "It is reinforced by unanimity rules only", "It is weakened by interpretation and implied powers"], "correctAnswer": "It is weakened by interpretation and implied powers", "explanation": "Conferral weakened by: effet utile flexibility clause implied powers This is a high-level critique  A/B/C → overly formalistic"}, {"question": "A Member State argues that subsidiarity was respected because the EU objective is important. Why is this flawed?", "options": ["Importance determines competence", "Subsidiarity applies only to exclusive competences", "Importance replaces proportionality", "Subsidiarity concerns effectiveness, not importance"], "correctAnswer": "Subsidiarity concerns effectiveness, not importance", "explanation": "Subsidiarity = effectiveness test, not importance  A → conferral issue B → wrong scope C → mixes principles"}, {"question": "Which scenario best challenges the boundary between shared and exclusive competences?", "options": ["EU adopts non-binding recommendations", "EU legislates in environment after Member States acted", "EU acts in customs union", "EU harmonises education policy"], "correctAnswer": "EU legislates in environment after Member States acted", "explanation": "Shared competence tension → overlap between EU + MS  C → clearly exclusive D → illegal (supporting competences don’t allow harmonisation) A → not relevant"}, {"question": "Which combination most strongly supports EU competence expansion?", "options": ["Proportionality + subsidiarity", "Exclusive competences only", "Effet utile + Article 352 + implied powers", "Conferral + subsidiarity"], "correctAnswer": "Effet utile + Article 352 + implied powers", "explanation": "These three mechanisms drive EU expansion This is a core exam insight  A/D → limiting principles B → static"}, {"question": "Which is the strongest argument that the EU resembles a state-like system?", "options": ["It uses treaties", "It has territory", "It depends on Member States", "It exercises binding powers over individuals"], "correctAnswer": "It exercises binding powers over individuals", "explanation": "Binding effect on individuals = key supranational feature  B → EU has no territory A/C → weak indicators"}, {"question": "Which scenario most clearly violates subsidiarity but NOT conferral?", "options": ["EU acts outside Treaty competences", "EU adopts measure without legal basis", "EU acts within shared competence unnecessarily", "EU acts in exclusive competence"], "correctAnswer": "EU acts within shared competence unnecessarily", "explanation": "EU has competence (conferral OK)BUT shouldn’t act → subsidiarity breach  A/B → conferral problems D → subsidiarity not applicable"}, {"question": "Which reasoning best reflects the CJEU’s approach to scope of EU law?", "options": ["Strict textual limitation", "Rejection of implied powers", "Preference for Member State autonomy", "Broad interpretation where EU law may be affected"], "correctAnswer": "Broad interpretation where EU law may be affected", "explanation": "CJEU uses broad interpretation Key phrase: potential effect on EU law  A/B/C → reflect restrictive or incorrect approaches"}]}}, {"id": "topic2", "title": "Sources of EU Law", "notesHtml": "<div class=\"notes-block\">\n<h3>1. Constituent Treaties (Primary Law of the European Union)</h3>\n<p>The constituent treaties form the primary law of the European Union and are at the top of the hierarchy of EU law.</p>\n<p>These include:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the Treaty on European Union (TEU)</li>\n<li>the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The TEU, originating from the Maastricht Treaty, is closer to a constitutional framework, while the TFEU is more detailed and regulates specific policies and areas of EU action.</p>\n<h3>2. The EU Charter of Fundamental Rights and Additional Components of Primary Law</h3>\n<p>The EU Charter of Fundamental Rights forms part of primary law through reference in Article 6 TEU.</p>\n<p>In addition to the Treaties, primary law also includes:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>annexes</li>\n<li>appendixes</li>\n<li>protocols</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>These are equally legally binding and are considered an integral part of EU primary law. For example, protocols may contain:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>rules on subsidiarity and proportionality</li>\n<li>the Statute of the Court of Justice of the European Union</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>special rules for certain Member States (for example, in relation to the euro or the Schengen system)</p>\n<h3>3. Structure of the TEU and TFEU</h3>\n<p>The structure of the Treaties reflects the division of functions within the EU legal system.</p>\n<p>The TEU contains:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>provisions on democratic principles</li>\n<li>institutional structure</li>\n<li>general principles</li>\n<li>The TFEU contains:</li>\n<li>types of secondary legislation</li>\n<li>legislative procedures</li>\n<li>rules on international agreements with third states</li>\n<li>In terms of organisation:</li>\n<li>the TEU is structured into titles, chapters, and sections</li>\n<li>the TFEU is structured into parts, titles, chapters, and sections</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>4. Treaty Revision Procedure (Article 48 TEU)</h3>\n<p>The procedure for revising the Treaties is set out in Article 48 TEU.</p>\n<h4>4.1 Proposal Stage</h4>\n<p>A proposal for Treaty revision may come from:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the European Commission</li>\n<li>the European Parliament</li>\n<li>Member States</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The proposal is submitted to the Council and then to the European Council. National parliaments are also notified.</p>\n<h4>4.2 Convention or Intergovernmental Conference</h4>\n<p>According to Article 48(3) TEU, the President of the European Council may convene a Convention, composed of:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>representatives of national parliaments</li>\n<li>heads of state or government</li>\n<li>representatives of the European Parliament and Commission</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>Alternatively, the process may proceed directly to a conference of Member States.</p>\n<h4>4.3 Adoption and Ratification</h4>\n<p>Proposed amendments are discussed in a conference of Member States (Article 48(4) TEU).</p>\n<p>Adoption requires:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>unanimity among Member States</li>\n<li>After adoption:</li>\n<li>each Member State must ratify the amendments according to its national constitutional procedures</li>\n<li>This may involve:</li>\n<li>referendums</li>\n<li>approval by national constitutional courts</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>5. General Principles of EU Law</h3>\n<p>General principles of EU law are primarily developed through the jurisprudence of the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU).</p>\n<p>They have developed over time and are partly codified in the Treaties, including:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Title I TEU (common provisions)</li>\n<li>Protocol on subsidiarity and proportionality</li>\n<li>TFEU provisions on non-discrimination</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h4>5.1 Function of General Principles</h4>\n<p>General principles serve several functions:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>they fill gaps in EU law</li>\n<li>they strengthen the autonomy and coherence of EU law</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>they guide the interpretation of primary and secondary law, as well as national law within the scope of EU law</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>they are used in the review of the legality of secondary legislation and international agreements</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h4>5.2 Sources of General Principles</h4>\n<p>General principles are derived from:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>general principles of international law</li>\n<li>common legal and constitutional traditions of Member States</li>\n<li>typical features of EU law inferred by the Court (such as subsidiarity)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h4>5.3 Examples of General Principles</h4>\n<p>General principles of EU law include:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>proportionality (case law since 1954; Article 5(4) TEU)</li>\n<li>subsidiarity (Article 5(3) TEU)</li>\n<li>respect for fundamental rights (Article 6(3) TEU)</li>\n<li>equal treatment (including case law such as Mangold; Article 19 TFEU and Article 21 of the Charter)</li>\n<li>legal certainty (including foreseeability)</li>\n<li>precautionary principle (in environmental policy)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>6. Hierarchy of Sources of EU Law</h3>\n<p>EU law follows a hierarchical structure of sources.</p>\n<p>This hierarchy consists of:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Constituent treaties (TEU, TFEU, and the Charter of Fundamental Rights through Article 6 TEU)</li>\n<li>General principles of EU law</li>\n<li>International agreements concluded by the EU</li>\n<li>Secondary legislation (such as regulations and directives)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>In EU law, the legality of lower-ranking norms depends on their compliance with higher-ranking norms. This hierarchical structure is essential in judicial review procedures.</p>\n<h3>7. Comparison with Public International Law (PIL)</h3>\n<p>Unlike EU law, public international law does not have a strict hierarchy of sources.</p>\n<p>According to Article 38 of the Statute of the International Court of Justice, the sources of international law include:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>treaties</li>\n<li>customary international law</li>\n<li>general principles of international law</li>\n<li>judicial decisions and scholarly writings</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>These sources do not have a strict hierarchy. However, some limited hierarchies exist in international law:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>jus cogens norms, which cannot be derogated from</li>\n<li>the principle that later norms prevail over earlier ones</li>\n<li>the principle that more specific norms prevail over more general ones</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>This contrasts with EU law, where hierarchy plays a central role in determining legality.</p>\n<h3>8. Case Law: CJEU, Mangold (Preliminary Ruling)</h3>\n<p>The Court of Justice of the European Union in Case C-144/04, Mangold dealt with the role of general principles of EU law.</p>\n<p>In this case:</p>\n<p>The Court could not rely directly on the directive because the transposition period had not yet expired.</p>\n<p>Instead, it held that the directive reflected general principles derived from international instruments and common constitutional traditions of Member States.</p>\n<p>The case raised controversy regarding whether the principle of non-discrimination could produce legal effects even before full implementation of the directive.</p>\n</div>", "quizData": {"easy": [{"question": "Which source of EU law is at the top of the hierarchy?", "options": ["General principles of EU law", "International agreements", "Constituent treaties (TEU & TFEU)", "Secondary legislation"], "correctAnswer": "Constituent treaties (TEU & TFEU)", "explanation": "Constituent treaties = top of EU hierarchy (primary law)  A → below treaties B → below general principles D → lowest level"}, {"question": "The EU Charter of Fundamental Rights is:", "options": ["Not legally binding", "Part of primary law through Article 6 TEU", "Secondary legislation", "A general principle only"], "correctAnswer": "Part of primary law through Article 6 TEU", "explanation": "EU Charter of Fundamental Rights is binding via Article 6 TEU → primary law  A → incorrect C → secondary law D → not just a principle"}, {"question": "Which of the following is considered primary law?", "options": ["Directives", "Recommendations", "Constituent treaties and protocols", "Regulations"], "correctAnswer": "Constituent treaties and protocols", "explanation": "Primary law = treaties + protocols  A/D → secondary law B → non-binding"}, {"question": "Which institution primarily develops general principles of EU law?", "options": ["European Commission", "Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU)", "European Council", "National courts"], "correctAnswer": "Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU)", "explanation": "CJEU develops general principles via case law  A/C → political bodies D → apply law, don’t create GP"}, {"question": "General principles of EU law serve which function?", "options": ["Fill gaps and aid interpretation", "Replace treaties", "Apply only internationally", "Only regulate institutions"], "correctAnswer": "Fill gaps and aid interpretation", "explanation": "GP functions: gap filling interpretation legality review  B/C/D → too narrow or incorrect"}, {"question": "Which of the following is a general principle of EU law?", "options": ["Direct applicability", "Qualified majority voting", "Proportionality", "Directives"], "correctAnswer": "Proportionality", "explanation": "Proportionality = classic general principle  A → feature of EU law B → procedure D → secondary law"}, {"question": "Which source ranks below general principles?", "options": ["Constituent treaties", "Protocols", "EU Charter", "International agreements"], "correctAnswer": "International agreements", "explanation": "Correct hierarchy:treaties > GP > intl agreements  A/B/C → higher sources"}, {"question": "Which statement about EU law hierarchy is correct?", "options": ["All sources are equal", "General principles are optional", "International agreements override treaties", "Secondary law must comply with higher sources"], "correctAnswer": "Secondary law must comply with higher sources", "explanation": "Core rule: lower sources must comply with higher ones  A → wrong (EU ≠ PIL) B → GP are binding C → treaties remain supreme"}, {"question": "Which article governs treaty revision procedures?", "options": ["Article 267 TFEU", "Article 48 TEU", "Article 218 TFEU", "Article 5 TEU"], "correctAnswer": "Article 48 TEU", "explanation": "Article 48 TEU = treaty revision"}, {"question": "International agreements in EU law refer to:", "options": ["Agreements between EU and third states/organisations", "Internal EU legislation", "National constitutions", "Treaties between Member States"], "correctAnswer": "Agreements between EU and third states/organisations", "explanation": "International agreements = EU + third states  others → incorrect scope"}], "medium": [{"question": "Which statement best reflects the hierarchy of EU law?", "options": ["No hierarchy exists", "General principles > treaties", "Treaties > general principles > international agreements > secondary law", "Secondary law > treaties"], "correctAnswer": "Treaties > general principles > international agreements > secondary law", "explanation": "Correct hierarchy:treaties → GP → intl agreements → secondary  A/D → reversed B → GP below treaties"}, {"question": "What is the key function of general principles?", "options": ["Create treaties", "Fill gaps, guide interpretation, and review legality", "Apply only externally", "Replace secondary law"], "correctAnswer": "Fill gaps, guide interpretation, and review legality", "explanation": "GP: fill gaps guide interpretation review legality  A/D → wrong role C → too narrow"}, {"question": "Which source contributes to the development of general principles?", "options": ["Only directives", "Only EU treaties", "Only CJEU decisions", "National constitutional traditions and international law"], "correctAnswer": "National constitutional traditions and international law", "explanation": "Sources of GP: international law MS constitutional traditions  A/B/C → incomplete"}, {"question": "Which statement about Mangold is correct?", "options": ["It establishes subsidiarity", "It concerns treaty revision", "It confirms equal treatment as a general principle of EU law", "It concerns primacy only"], "correctAnswer": "It confirms equal treatment as a general principle of EU law", "explanation": "Mangold v Helm: equal treatment = general principle applied before directive deadline  others → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which statement about international agreements is correct?", "options": ["They are not binding", "They rank above secondary law but below general principles", "They rank above treaties", "They are below secondary law"], "correctAnswer": "They rank above secondary law but below general principles", "explanation": "International agreements: above secondary law below GP  A → false C → too high D → too low"}, {"question": "What is the key contribution of the ERTA case?", "options": ["Establishing subsidiarity", "Establishing primacy", "Establishing direct effect", "Establishing implied external competences of the EU"], "correctAnswer": "Establishing implied external competences of the EU", "explanation": "ERTA: internal competence → external competence  A/B/C → different doctrines"}, {"question": "When does the EU have exclusive competence externally?", "options": ["Never", "When it has exercised internal competence in that field", "Always", "Only with MS approval"], "correctAnswer": "When it has exercised internal competence in that field", "explanation": "EU gains exclusive external competence when it acts internally  A/C/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "What are mixed agreements?", "options": ["Agreements between Member States", "Non-binding agreements", "Agreements involving EU + MS + third countries", "Internal agreements"], "correctAnswer": "Agreements involving EU + MS + third countries", "explanation": "Mixed agreements = EU + MS + third states  A → MS only B → binding agreements D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which procedure applies to most international agreements?", "options": ["Unanimity always", "Referendum", "Judicial decision", "Qualified majority in the Council"], "correctAnswer": "Qualified majority in the Council", "explanation": "Default rule: qualified majority voting  A → only in specific cases B/C → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Who can request a CJEU opinion?", "options": ["Only Commission", "Only courts", "Member States, Commission, Council, Parliament", "Only Member States"], "correctAnswer": "Member States, Commission, Council, Parliament", "explanation": "Multiple actors can request CJEU opinion  A/B/D → too restrictive"}], "hard": [{"question": "A regulation conflicts with a general principle of EU law. Outcome?", "options": ["Both apply", "Member State decides", "General principle prevails, regulation invalidated", "Regulation prevails"], "correctAnswer": "General principle prevails, regulation invalidated", "explanation": "GP > secondary law → regulation invalid  A/D → ignore hierarchy B → MS irrelevant"}, {"question": "Why does EU law have a clear hierarchy?", "options": ["EU law is political", "EU law requires legality review of lower norms against higher ones", "EU law lacks structure", "PIL has stronger hierarchy"], "correctAnswer": "EU law requires legality review of lower norms against higher ones", "explanation": "EU hierarchy allows legality review of lower norms Key difference from public international law  A/C/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "A Member State refuses treaty revision ratification. Result?", "options": ["CJEU decides", "Revision proceeds", "Parliament overrides", "Revision fails (unanimity required)"], "correctAnswer": "Revision fails (unanimity required)", "explanation": "Treaty revision requires unanimity  A/B/C → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which scenario shows implied external competence?", "options": ["EU gains external competence via internal competence", "EU signs without competence", "MS act independently", "No agreement"], "correctAnswer": "EU gains external competence via internal competence", "explanation": "ERTA logic:internal competence → external competence  others → incorrect"}, {"question": "Status of general principles?", "options": ["Below secondary law", "Equal to treaties", "Above intl agreements but below treaties", "Optional"], "correctAnswer": "Above intl agreements but below treaties", "explanation": "GP sit between: treaties (above) intl agreements (below)  others → wrong hierarchy"}, {"question": "Directive vs international agreement conflict?", "options": ["Directive prevails", "No hierarchy", "International agreement prevails", "MS law prevails"], "correctAnswer": "International agreement prevails", "explanation": "Intl agreements prevail over directives  A → wrong B → hierarchy exists D → MS law irrelevant"}, {"question": "Mangold reasoning?", "options": ["Directive alone applied", "GP applied before deadline", "MS law prevails", "Treaties only matter"], "correctAnswer": "GP applied before deadline", "explanation": "Mangold: GP applied even before directive transposition Very examinable nuance  others → incorrect"}, {"question": "Example of hierarchical review?", "options": ["Treaties reviewed by directives", "Recommendations override regulations", "National law overrides EU law", "Secondary law checked against treaties & GP"], "correctAnswer": "Secondary law checked against treaties & GP", "explanation": "Hierarchical review = checking secondary law vs higher norms  A/B/C → incorrect"}, {"question": "Article 218 TFEU governs:", "options": ["Treaty revision", "Directives", "Competences", "International agreements procedure"], "correctAnswer": "International agreements procedure", "explanation": "Article 218 TFEU = international agreements procedure  others → different provisions"}, {"question": "Internal vs external competence relationship?", "options": ["External always requires unanimity", "They are independent", "Internal competence generates external competence", "Depends on MS"], "correctAnswer": "Internal competence generates external competence", "explanation": "Internal competence generates external competence (ERTA)  A/B/D → incorrect"}]}}, {"id": "topic3", "title": "EU Secondary Legislation", "notesHtml": "<div class=\"notes-block\">\n<h3>1. Legislative and Non-Legislative Acts</h3>\n<p>Legislative acts are adopted following a legislative procedure. The ordinary legislative procedure is provided in Article 289 TFEU (see class on institutions).</p>\n<p>Non-legislative acts are adopted on the basis of delegated or implementing powers. These are regulated in Articles 290–291 TFEU. This is only to provide the full picture and is not part of the core course material.</p>\n<h3>2. Article 288 TFEU: Overview of EU Legal Acts</h3>\n<p>In order to exercise the Union’s competences, the institutions shall adopt:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>regulations, which are legally binding</li>\n<li>directives, which are legally binding</li>\n<li>decisions, which are legally binding</li>\n<li>recommendations and opinions, which are not legally binding</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>3. Regulations (Article 288 TFEU, second paragraph)</h3>\n<p>Regulations always have general application. This means they are binding on all Member States, all public authorities, and all private parties within those Member States.</p>\n<p>They are binding in their entirety, meaning that they become immediately and “forcefully” part of the national legal order of Member States. No further transposition into national law is needed and, importantly, it is not allowed. However, in some cases, Member States may still need to adopt complementary measures.</p>\n<p>Regulations are directly applicable in Member States. This reflects the requirement that EU law follows a monist approach. However, direct applicability is not the same as direct effect. Direct effect depends on whether a provision is sufficiently clear, precise, and unconditional.</p>\n<p>Regulations operate like “Union laws”, meaning they are the closest equivalent to what is typically understood as legislation. They are immediately binding on both public authorities and private parties.</p>\n<h3>4. Directives (Article 288 TFEU, third paragraph)</h3>\n<p>Directives are binding on the Member States to which they are addressed. They can sometimes be addressed to specific Member States, but in most cases they are addressed to all Member States, meaning that they usually, but not always, have general application.</p>\n<p>Directives are not directly binding on private parties.</p>\n<p>Directives require Member States to achieve a specific result by a certain deadline (the transposition period). However, Member States are free to choose the form and methods used to achieve that result. In practice, directives can sometimes also be very detailed regarding the methods to be used.</p>\n<p>During the transposition period, Member States have a standstill obligation, meaning that they must not adopt measures that would move away from achieving the directive’s objective. Instead, they must move forward in implementing it.</p>\n<p>This obligation is comparable to Article 18 of the Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties (VCLT) in public international law, which requires states to refrain from acts that would defeat the object and purpose of a treaty after signing or expressing consent to be bound.</p>\n<h3>5. Failure to Transpose Directives</h3>\n<p>After the transposition deadline, a failure to fully implement a directive constitutes an infringement of EU law.</p>\n<p>Regulations achieve the highest level of harmonisation, since they apply uniformly and immediately. Directives also contribute to harmonisation, but they leave room for diversity in national legal traditions. This is often preferred by Member States because it allows them more discretion.</p>\n<p>According to the principle of proportionality, the Union should not go beyond what is necessary to achieve its objectives. Therefore, the Union should use regulations only when directives are not sufficient.</p>\n<h3>6. CJEU, Mangold: Obligations During the Transposition Period</h3>\n<p>In the Mangold judgment, the Court identified two key obligations that Member States have before the transposition deadline expires:</p>\n<p>Member States have a standstill obligation, meaning that they must refrain from adopting measures that would negatively affect the achievement of the directive’s objective (paragraphs 67 and 72).</p>\n<p>Member States must take progressive steps during the transposition period to realise the directive’s objective (paragraphs 71 and 72).</p>\n<p>In other words, as paragraph 72 concludes, Member States must use the transposition period to align their national laws with the directive’s objectives. It would undermine the purpose of the directive if states were allowed to adopt measures that go against its objective.</p>\n<p>Therefore:</p>\n<p>Member States must not act against the directive’s objective.</p>\n<p>Member States must make progress towards achieving it.</p>\n<h3>7. Decisions (Article 288 TFEU, fourth paragraph)</h3>\n<p>Decisions are binding in their entirety, meaning that they immediately become part of the national legal order. No further transposition is required or allowed.</p>\n<p>However, decisions do not have general application. They are binding only on those to whom they are addressed. This may include:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Member States</li>\n<li>private parties (individuals or firms)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>8. Recommendations and Opinions</h3>\n<p>Recommendations and opinions are not legally binding.</p>\n<p>They often take the form of guidelines, communications, or notices. Although they are not binding, the CJEU may reclassify them as regulations, directives, or decisions if their content effectively produces binding legal effects.</p>\n<p>These instruments are typically used in areas where the Union has only supporting competences, meaning that it can support, coordinate, or complement Member States’ actions but cannot adopt binding legislation.</p>\n<p>According to Articles 5 and 6 TFEU, supporting competences represent a lower level of EU authority.</p>\n<h3>9. Example: Recommendations in Public Health (Article 168 TFEU)</h3>\n<p>Article 168 TFEU provides that a high level of human health protection must be ensured in all Union policies. The Union may complement national policies and may adopt recommendations.</p>\n<p>Examples of recommendations adopted by the Council include:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>prevention of alcohol consumption among young people (2001)</li>\n<li>cancer screening (2003)</li>\n<li>action in the field of rare diseases (2009)</li>\n<li>smoke-free environments (2009)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>10. Comparison of EU Legal Instruments</h3>\n<h4>10.1 Regulation vs Decision</h4>\n<p>Both are legally binding and binding in their entirety. This means they are immediately part of the national legal order and do not require transposition.</p>\n<p>However, regulations always have general application, meaning they apply to all Member States and all individuals. Decisions do not have general application; they apply only to those to whom they are addressed.</p>\n<h4>10.2 Regulation vs Directive</h4>\n<p>Both are legally binding.</p>\n<p>Regulations are binding in their entirety and apply immediately without transposition. Directives are not binding in their entirety; they require transposition and allow Member States to choose how to achieve the objective.</p>\n<p>Regulations always have general application. Directives usually have general application but may be addressed to specific Member States. Directives bind only Member States and not private parties directly, whereas regulations bind both.</p>\n<h4>10.3 Decision vs Directive</h4>\n<p>Both are legally binding and may have a targeted approach.</p>\n<p>Decisions bind only those to whom they are addressed, including Member States and private parties. Directives bind only Member States, although they may apply to all or some of them.</p>\n<h4>10.4 Binding Acts vs Recommendations</h4>\n<p>Regulations, directives, and decisions are legally binding. Regulations and decisions are binding in their entirety, while directives require transposition but still impose legal obligations on Member States.</p>\n<p>Recommendations are not legally binding. They are used where the Union has only supporting competences and cannot adopt binding legislation.</p>\n<h3>11. Choice Between Regulation and Directive</h3>\n<p>Regulations and directives are the two main tools for acts of general application.</p>\n<p>When the Treaty does not prescribe which instrument to use, a choice must be made.</p>\n<p>The Commission often prefers regulations because they ensure uniformity. Member States often prefer directives because they allow flexibility and respect national traditions.</p>\n<p>This choice is also guided by the principle of proportionality.</p>\n<h3>12. Enforcement and Compliance</h3>\n<p>The European Commission monitors:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>whether directives are transposed by the deadline</li>\n<li>whether transposition is correct</li>\n<li>whether regulations require complementary measures</li>\n<li>If Member States fail to comply, infringement procedures may be initiated. These include:</li>\n<li>letters of formal notice</li>\n<li>reasoned opinions</li>\n<li>referral to the CJEU</li>\n</ul></div>\n</div>", "quizData": {"easy": [{"question": "Which of the following is NOT legally binding under Article 288 TFEU?", "options": ["Regulation", "Directive", "Recommendation", "Decision"], "correctAnswer": "Recommendation", "explanation": "Recommendations are not legally binding under Article 288 TFEU  A/B/D → all are binding acts👉 classic trap: students forget decisions are binding"}, {"question": "Which statement best describes a regulation?", "options": ["Binding only on Member States", "Binding in its entirety and directly applicable", "Requires transposition into national law", "Not binding on private parties"], "correctAnswer": "Binding in its entirety and directly applicable", "explanation": "Regulations are: binding in entirety directly applicable no transposition needed  C → describes directives D → regulations bind private parties too A → too narrow"}, {"question": "Which of the following is TRUE about directives?", "options": ["They are directly binding on private parties", "They require no implementation", "They bind Member States as to the result to be achieved", "They always have specific application"], "correctAnswer": "They bind Member States as to the result to be achieved", "explanation": "Directives bind MS as to the result, not methods  A → no direct binding on private parties B → they require implementation D → often general, not always specific"}, {"question": "Which act is binding only on those to whom it is addressed?", "options": ["Regulation", "Directive", "Recommendation", "Decision"], "correctAnswer": "Decision", "explanation": "Decisions = binding only on those addressed  A → regulations = general application B → directives often general C → not binding"}, {"question": "What is the key feature of direct applicability?", "options": ["EU law must be transposed", "EU law automatically forms part of national law", "EU law applies only after court confirmation", "EU law binds only institutions"], "correctAnswer": "EU law automatically forms part of national law", "explanation": "Direct applicability = automatic integration into national law  A → transposition applies to directives C/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which statement about regulations is correct?", "options": ["They require implementation by Member States", "They allow national variation", "They always have general application", "They are not binding on individuals"], "correctAnswer": "They always have general application", "explanation": "Regulations always have general application  A → directives B → opposite (regulations ensure uniformity) D → wrong"}, {"question": "Directives are primarily addressed to:", "options": ["Private companies", "Member States", "EU institutions only", "Courts"], "correctAnswer": "Member States", "explanation": "Directives are addressed to Member States  A → no direct horizontal binding C/D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Which act provides the highest level of harmonisation?", "options": ["Directive", "Decision", "Recommendation", "Regulation"], "correctAnswer": "Regulation", "explanation": "Regulations = highest harmonisation (uniform rules)  A → directives allow variation B/C → not general harmonisation tools"}, {"question": "What happens if a directive is not fully transposed by the deadline?", "options": ["It becomes invalid", "It is optional", "It constitutes an infringement of EU law", "It automatically becomes a regulation"], "correctAnswer": "It constitutes an infringement of EU law", "explanation": "Failure to transpose = infringement of EU law  A/B → no D → incorrect transformation"}, {"question": "Which act is most similar to national legislation (“laws”)?", "options": ["Directive", "Recommendation", "Decision", "Regulation"], "correctAnswer": "Regulation", "explanation": "Regulations operate like “Union laws”  A → requires MS action B → non-binding C → targeted"}], "medium": [{"question": "Which statement best reflects the difference between regulations and directives?", "options": ["Regulations require transposition, directives do not", "Regulations are binding in result only", "Directives allow Member States discretion in implementation", "Directives bind private parties directly"], "correctAnswer": "Directives allow Member States discretion in implementation", "explanation": "Directives = result binding + MS discretion  A → reversed B → describes regulations D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which obligation applies to Member States before the transposition deadline of a directive?", "options": ["Immediate full implementation", "Standstill obligation (no measures undermining the directive)", "No obligation at all", "Judicial enforcement only"], "correctAnswer": "Standstill obligation (no measures undermining the directive)", "explanation": "Standstill obligation: no undermining directive progress required  C → incorrect (there are obligations) A/D → wrong timing"}, {"question": "Which case established obligations during the transposition period?", "options": ["Van Gend en Loos", "Costa v ENEL", "Mangold", "Francovich"], "correctAnswer": "Mangold", "explanation": "Mangold v Helm established: standstill progress obligation  others → unrelated doctrines"}, {"question": "What is the standstill obligation?", "options": ["Suspend all national legislation", "Avoid measures that compromise the directive’s objective", "Fully implement the directive immediately", "Wait until the deadline"], "correctAnswer": "Avoid measures that compromise the directive’s objective", "explanation": "Standstill = no measures undermining directive  A → too extreme C → not required D → opposite"}, {"question": "Which of the following is TRUE about decisions?", "options": ["They always have general application", "They are not binding", "They bind only those to whom they are addressed", "They require transposition"], "correctAnswer": "They bind only those to whom they are addressed", "explanation": "Decisions: binding targeted no general application  A → wrong B → false D → no transposition"}, {"question": "Why are directives often preferred under proportionality?", "options": ["They are stronger legally", "They allow flexibility for Member States", "They are easier to annul", "They avoid infringement procedures"], "correctAnswer": "They allow flexibility for Member States", "explanation": "Directives = less intrusive → more proportionate  A → not about strength C/D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Which act can be requalified by the CJEU despite its label?", "options": ["Regulation", "Directive", "Recommendation", "Treaty"], "correctAnswer": "Recommendation", "explanation": "CJEU can requalify recommendations based on substance  A/B → already binding D → not relevant"}, {"question": "Which is TRUE regarding recommendations?", "options": ["They are legally binding", "They are used in exclusive competences", "They are typically used in supporting competences", "They require transposition"], "correctAnswer": "They are typically used in supporting competences", "explanation": "Recommendations used in supporting competences  A → not binding B → exclusive competences require binding acts D → no transposition"}, {"question": "What is a key difference between decisions and directives?", "options": ["Decisions are not binding", "Directives can address private parties", "Decisions can address private parties, directives cannot", "Directives are more specific"], "correctAnswer": "Decisions can address private parties, directives cannot", "explanation": "Decisions can target: MS individuals Directives → only MS  A → decisions are binding B → incorrect D → not key difference"}, {"question": "Which statement best reflects harmonisation differences?", "options": ["Directives ensure complete uniformity", "Regulations allow diversity", "Directives allow some national variation, regulations do not", "Both operate identically"], "correctAnswer": "Directives allow some national variation, regulations do not", "explanation": "Regulations = uniformityDirectives = flexibility  A/B/D → incorrect"}], "hard": [{"question": "A Member State adopts legislation during the transposition period that contradicts a directive’s objective. What is the strongest legal assessment?", "options": ["No issue until deadline", "Breach of standstill obligation", "Only a proportionality issue", "Only relevant after implementation"], "correctAnswer": "Breach of standstill obligation", "explanation": "Breach of standstill obligation (Mangold) Key: applies before deadline  A/D → wrong (obligations already exist) C → wrong principle"}, {"question": "Which scenario best reflects incorrect use of a regulation under proportionality?", "options": ["Regulation used for uniform rules where variation is needed", "Directive used where uniformity is required", "Regulation used where a directive would suffice", "Directive used incorrectly"], "correctAnswer": "Regulation used where a directive would suffice", "explanation": "Regulation used when directive sufficient = disproportionate Links to proportionality principle  A → vague B → opposite issue D → unclear"}, {"question": "Which statement best reflects the legal nature of directives before the deadline?", "options": ["They have no legal effect", "They impose obligations to avoid undermining their objective", "They are fully binding", "They are optional"], "correctAnswer": "They impose obligations to avoid undermining their objective", "explanation": "Before deadline: no full effect BUT obligations exist (standstill + progress)  A → too absolute C → incorrect D → false"}, {"question": "A recommendation is challenged before the CJEU. What is the most accurate statement?", "options": ["It cannot be reviewed", "It is always non-binding", "It may be requalified as a binding act depending on content", "It automatically becomes a directive"], "correctAnswer": "It may be requalified as a binding act depending on content", "explanation": "CJEU looks at substance over label recommendation can become binding act  B → too formalistic A/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which combination correctly reflects binding force and application?", "options": ["Directive = binding in entirety", "Regulation = binding in entirety + general application", "Decision = general application", "Recommendation = binding on MS"], "correctAnswer": "Regulation = binding in entirety + general application", "explanation": "Regulation: binding in entirety general application  A → describes regulations, not directives C → decisions are targeted D → recommendations not binding"}, {"question": "Which scenario best reflects infringement proceedings?", "options": ["Directive adopted incorrectly", "Regulation not followed by MS", "Failure to transpose directive correctly by deadline", "Recommendation ignored"], "correctAnswer": "Failure to transpose directive correctly by deadline", "explanation": "Classic infringement: failure to transpose correctly  B → also possible but less typical exam focus A → vague D → not binding"}, {"question": "Which statement best captures the relationship between regulations and directives?", "options": ["They are identical in legal effect", "Regulations allow flexibility", "Directives require uniform application", "Regulations ensure uniformity; directives allow diversity"], "correctAnswer": "Regulations ensure uniformity; directives allow diversity", "explanation": "Core distinction: regulation = uniformity directive = flexibility  others → reversed or wrong"}, {"question": "Which is the strongest argument that directives respect Member State sovereignty?", "options": ["They are not binding", "They allow choice of form and methods", "They apply to individuals", "They require no implementation"], "correctAnswer": "They allow choice of form and methods", "explanation": "Directives respect sovereignty:→ MS choose form + methods  A → false C → irrelevant D → wrong"}, {"question": "Which scenario best illustrates direct applicability but not necessarily direct effect?", "options": ["Directive before deadline", "Regulation that is unclear or conditional", "Recommendation", "Decision"], "correctAnswer": "Regulation that is unclear or conditional", "explanation": "Regulation = directly applicableBUT needs: clarity precision unconditionality for direct effect  A → directive issue C → not applicable D → different concept"}, {"question": "Which reasoning best reflects the legal hierarchy of EU acts?", "options": ["All acts have equal binding force", "Regulations, directives, and decisions are binding; recommendations are not", "Directives are stronger than regulations", "Recommendations override directives"], "correctAnswer": "Regulations, directives, and decisions are binding; recommendations are not", "explanation": "Legal hierarchy under Article 288: binding: regulations, directives, decisions non-binding: recommendations  A → false C/D → incorrect"}]}}, {"id": "topic4", "title": "Specific Features of EU Law: Direct Effect and Primacy", "notesHtml": "<div class=\"notes-block\">\n<h3>1. Autonomy of EU Law</h3>\n<p>Due to Member States having limited their sovereign powers and due to the existence of a sophisticated institutional structure, a “new legal order” or “own legal system” has been created, which is peculiar to EU law.</p>\n<p>A significant transfer of sovereign powers to the EU has created a very special, distinct and independent body of EU law, which is autonomous from public international law. The constituent treaties do not resemble ordinary international treaties, because they establish a very detailed and sophisticated institutional structure, including both law-making and enforcement powers of EU institutions.</p>\n<p>In addition, the EU legal system is self-referential, meaning that it does not need to rely on public international law to govern itself. This is unprecedented. However, this does not mean that the EU is completely detached from public international law. According to Article 3(5) TEU, the Union shall contribute to the development of international law.</p>\n<p>Within this framework, the transfer of sovereign powers is also visible in the powers of the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU), which plays a central and crucial role in the day-to-day interpretation, application, and development of EU law.</p>\n<p>EU law is also autonomous from national legal systems. This is visible in:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>direct applicability of EU law (monist approach required by the EU)</li>\n<li>the principles of direct effect and primacy developed by the CJEU</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>Therefore, the autonomy of EU law is a crucial building block for the doctrines of direct effect and primacy.</p>\n<h3>2. Direct Applicability of EU Law</h3>\n<p>A special feature of EU law is that it does not allow Member States to choose between monism and dualism. Member States are obliged to adopt a monist approach.</p>\n<p>This means that all EU law is directly applicable, in the sense that all EU law forms part of the national legal order. EU law and national legal orders operate within the same framework.</p>\n<p>Therefore, EU law is a distinct legal order which forms an integral part of the legal systems of Member States.</p>\n<p>Direct applicability is the basis upon which the EU developed the doctrines of direct effect and primacy.</p>\n<p>It is important to distinguish that:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>all EU law is directly applicable</li>\n<li>but not all EU law has direct effect</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>If a provision has direct effect, this means that an individual has the ability to invoke that provision before national administrations or national courts in order to make use of EU law that is in their favour.</p>\n<p>Direct effect depends on whether national administrations and courts can apply the provision immediately, without requiring further measures. Therefore, the provision must not depend on additional clarification or implementation. It must already be sufficiently clear, precise, and unconditional.</p>\n<p>Direct effect is determined by the quality of the formulation of a specific provision, not by its subject matter. The Court of Justice of the European Union has the final authority in determining whether a provision has sufficient quality to produce direct effect.</p>\n<h4>2.1 Types of Direct Effect</h4>\n<p>A provision may have two types of direct effect:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Vertical direct effect, where a provision can be invoked by an individual against a Member State</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>Horizontal direct effect, where a provision can be invoked by an individual against another individual or private party</p>\n<h3>3. Case Law: CJEU, Van Gend en Loos</h3>\n<p>The Court of Justice of the European Union in Case 26/62, Van Gend en Loos established the doctrine of direct effect and clarified the nature of EU law.</p>\n<p>From this judgment, the following key points emerge:</p>\n<p>First, the EEC Treaty does not merely create mutual obligations between states like ordinary international treaties. Instead, due to the transfer of sovereign powers from Member States to EU institutions, it creates an autonomous legal order which affects not only Member States but also their citizens.</p>\n<p>Second, the existence of the preliminary ruling procedure (Article 267 TFEU) shows that individuals must be able to invoke EU law before national courts. Otherwise, national courts would not be confronted with questions of EU law.</p>\n<p>Third, a new legal order of international law has been created, where Member States limit their sovereign rights in certain fields, and where the subjects of law include not only states but also their nationals.</p>\n<p>Fourth, EU law autonomously confers rights and obligations on individuals independently of national legislation. Because EU law forms part of national legal systems, it becomes part of the legal heritage of individuals. Therefore, obligations imposed on Member States translate into rights for individuals.</p>\n<p>Fifth, the wording of the provision in question was sufficiently clear and unconditional. It imposed a negative obligation on states and did not require further implementation, meaning that it had sufficient quality to produce direct effect.</p>\n<p>Sixth, obligations imposed on Member States translate into rights for individuals, which allows individuals to invoke these obligations before national courts. This creates vertical direct effect.</p>\n<p>Seventh, denying individuals the possibility to invoke EU law would undermine the effectiveness of the entire EU legal system. This reflects the principle of effectiveness (effet utile).</p>\n<p>Eighth, through direct effect, national courts contribute, together with the Commission and Member States, to the supervision and enforcement of EU law.</p>\n<h3>4. Direct Effect of Different Types of EU Acts</h3>\n<h4>4.1 Direct Effect of Regulations</h4>\n<p>Regulations are binding in their entirety, meaning that they are immediately part of the national legal order. Transposition is neither required nor allowed.</p>\n<p>This feature makes regulations appear particularly suitable for direct effect. However, direct effect still depends on the quality of each specific provision. The provision must be clear, precise, and unconditional.</p>\n<p>If a regulation requires complementary measures, it cannot produce direct effect.</p>\n<h4>4.2 Direct Effect of Decisions</h4>\n<p>Decisions are also binding in their entirety and become part of the national legal order when they are addressed to Member States. This makes them appear suitable for direct effect.</p>\n<p>However, as with regulations, each provision must be assessed individually. Only provisions that are clear, precise, and unconditional can produce direct effect.</p>\n<p>Decisions do not have general application. They are binding only on specific Member States, individuals, or private parties.</p>\n<p>As a general rule:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>decisions can have vertical direct effect</li>\n<li>decisions addressed to private parties do not produce horizontal direct effect</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>If a decision is addressed directly to private parties, it can produce direct effect for those parties.</p>\n<h4>4.3 Direct Effect of Directives</h4>\n<p>Directives are not binding in their entirety. They require Member States to achieve a specific result within a certain period (the transposition period).</p>\n<p>This makes directives less likely to produce direct effect. However, directives can have direct effect under specific conditions.</p>\n<p>A directive may produce direct effect only:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>if it is clear, precise, and unconditional</li>\n<li>if the transposition period has expired</li>\n<li>if it has not been properly implemented</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>Directives can only produce vertical direct effect, meaning they can be invoked by individuals against the state.</p>\n<p>They cannot produce horizontal direct effect between individuals.</p>\n<p>When an individual wishes to rely on a directive against another individual, but cannot because the directive has not been implemented, the solution lies in:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the principle of primacy</li>\n<li>the duty of consistent interpretation</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>National courts must interpret national law in light of the wording and purpose of the directive.</p>\n<h3>5. Primacy of EU Law</h3>\n<h4>5.1 Foundations of Primacy</h4>\n<p>The principle of primacy is based on:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the limitation of Member States’ sovereign rights</li>\n<li>the special and original nature of EU law as a new legal order</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>This implies that EU law has primacy over domestic legal provisions, regardless of the level of the national norm.</p>\n<p>However, primacy applies only within the fields where competences have been conferred on the EU.</p>\n<h4>5.2 Relationship Between Primacy and Direct Effect</h4>\n<p>Primacy presupposes direct effect.</p>\n<p>Direct effect allows EU law to be applied directly before national courts. Without direct effect, EU law could not be applied as such, and primacy would be meaningless.</p>\n<p>Therefore:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>without direct effect, national courts could not apply EU law instead of national law</li>\n<li>direct effect enables primacy to function</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The ability of national courts to disapply national law ensures the effectiveness of primacy.</p>\n<h4>5.3 Primacy and Consistent Interpretation</h4>\n<p>For consistent interpretation, direct effect is not required.</p>\n<p>National courts must interpret national law in a way that is consistent with EU law, even if EU law does not have direct effect. This is possible because all EU law has direct applicability and forms part of national legal systems.</p>\n<h3>6. Case Law: CJEU, Costa v ENEL</h3>\n<p>The Court of Justice of the European Union in Case 6/64, Costa v ENEL established the principle of primacy.</p>\n<p>The Court held that, unlike ordinary international treaties, the EU has created an autonomous legal order due to the transfer of sovereign rights to its institutions. This legal order forms an integral part of the legal systems of Member States and binds both states and their nationals.</p>\n<p>Because EU law is already part of national legal systems, Member States cannot give priority to later national laws based on the principle of reciprocity. Reciprocity (conditional loyalty) does not operate in EU law.</p>\n<p>Allowing national law to prevail over EU law would undermine the principle of direct applicability and threaten the legal foundation of the EU. Therefore, primacy is essential for the functioning of the EU.</p>\n<h3>7. Principle of Sincere Cooperation</h3>\n<p>The principle of sincere cooperation is laid down in Article 4(3) TEU.</p>\n<p>It corresponds to the principle of good faith in public international law (Article 26 of the Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties).</p>\n<p>Under this principle, Member States must:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>take all necessary measures to ensure fulfilment of EU obligations</li>\n<li>not jeopardise the objectives of the Union</li>\n<li>contribute to the achievement of Union tasks</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>8. Principle of Effectiveness (Effet Utile)</h3>\n<p>The Court of Justice uses the principle of effectiveness (effet utile) as an interpretative principle.</p>\n<p>This principle requires that EU law be interpreted in a way that ensures its practical effectiveness.</p>\n<p>For example, in Case C-144/04, Mangold, the Court relied on effectiveness when dealing with a directive before the expiry of its transposition period, reflecting similar logic to Article 18 of the Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties.</p>\n<h3>9. Doctrine of Consistent Interpretation</h3>\n<p>The doctrine of consistent interpretation requires that national law be interpreted in light of:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the wording of EU law</li>\n<li>the purpose of EU law</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>This obligation applies as far as possible, even where EU law does not have direct effect.</p>\n</div>", "quizData": {"easy": [{"question": "What does the autonomy of EU law mean?", "options": ["EU law depends on national law", "EU law is independent from both national law and public international law", "EU law only applies through treaties", "EU law requires state consent for each application"], "correctAnswer": "EU law is independent from both national law and public international law", "explanation": "Autonomy = EU law is a distinct legal order, independent from both national law and traditional public international law  A → opposite C → too narrow D → contradicts autonomy"}, {"question": "Which statement best describes direct applicability?", "options": ["EU law must be transposed into national law", "EU law automatically forms part of national legal systems", "EU law only applies after court recognition", "EU law applies only to Member States"], "correctAnswer": "EU law automatically forms part of national legal systems", "explanation": "Direct applicability = EU law automatically becomes part of national law  A → directives C → incorrect D → too limited"}, {"question": "Which statement is correct?", "options": ["All EU law has direct effect", "No EU law has direct effect", "All EU law is directly applicable, but not all has direct effect", "Direct applicability depends on clarity"], "correctAnswer": "All EU law is directly applicable, but not all has direct effect", "explanation": "Core rule: all EU law = directly applicable NOT all = directly effective Fundamental distinction  A/B → extremes D → describes direct effect, not applicability"}, {"question": "Which of the following is required for direct effect?", "options": ["Democratic legitimacy", "Clear, precise, and unconditional provision", "Adoption by national courts", "General application"], "correctAnswer": "Clear, precise, and unconditional provision", "explanation": "Direct effect requires: clear precise unconditional Determined by CJEU  A/C/D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Vertical direct effect means:", "options": ["EU law applies between institutions", "EU law applies between Member States", "Individuals invoke EU law against the state", "Individuals invoke EU law against other individuals"], "correctAnswer": "Individuals invoke EU law against the state", "explanation": "Vertical direct effect = individual vs state  D → horizontal A/B → incorrect relationships"}, {"question": "Horizontal direct effect refers to:", "options": ["State vs state", "Individual vs state", "Individual vs individual", "Institution vs state"], "correctAnswer": "Individual vs individual", "explanation": "Horizontal direct effect = individual vs individual  B → vertical A/D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Which case established the principle of direct effect?", "options": ["Costa v ENEL", "Van Gend en Loos", "Mangold", "Francovich"], "correctAnswer": "Van Gend en Loos", "explanation": "Van Gend en Loos established direct effect  A → primacy C → different doctrine D → state liability"}, {"question": "Which principle ensures EU law prevails over national law?", "options": ["Direct effect", "Subsidiarity", "Primacy", "Proportionality"], "correctAnswer": "Primacy", "explanation": "Primacy = EU law prevails over national law  A → enforceability B/D → unrelated"}, {"question": "What is the role of national courts in EU law?", "options": ["Only apply national law", "Ignore EU law", "Apply EU law and ensure its effectiveness", "Refer all cases to the CJEU"], "correctAnswer": "Apply EU law and ensure its effectiveness", "explanation": "National courts: apply EU law ensure effectiveness Key enforcement role  A/B → incorrect D → too absolute"}, {"question": "Which principle requires Member States not to undermine EU objectives?", "options": ["Proportionality", "Conferral", "Sincere cooperation", "Supremacy"], "correctAnswer": "Sincere cooperation", "explanation": "Article 4(3) TEU→ MS must not undermine EU objectives  A/B → wrong principles D → primacy ≠ cooperation"}], "medium": [{"question": "Which statement best explains why EU law is autonomous?", "options": ["It relies on international law", "It forms a new legal order with its own institutions and norms", "It is subordinate to national law", "It only governs states"], "correctAnswer": "It forms a new legal order with its own institutions and norms", "explanation": "EU law = new legal order with: transfer of sovereignty own institutions self-referential system  A/C/D → contradict autonomy"}, {"question": "Which statement best captures the relationship between direct applicability and direct effect?", "options": ["They are identical", "Direct applicability requires direct effect", "Direct effect requires direct applicability", "Neither are related"], "correctAnswer": "Direct effect requires direct applicability", "explanation": "Direct effect requires:➡ EU law already part of national law (direct applicability) So: applicability → foundation  A → false B → reversed D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which provision is most likely to have direct effect?", "options": ["A vague policy objective", "A provision requiring further legislation", "A clear and unconditional prohibition", "A recommendation"], "correctAnswer": "A clear and unconditional prohibition", "explanation": "Clear + unconditional prohibition = classic direct effect scenario (Van Gend en Loos logic)  A/B → too vague D → not binding"}, {"question": "Which statement about regulations and direct effect is correct?", "options": ["All regulations automatically have direct effect", "Regulations never have direct effect", "Regulations may have direct effect depending on the provision", "Regulations require transposition"], "correctAnswer": "Regulations may have direct effect depending on the provision", "explanation": "Regulations ≠ automatically directly effective Must still satisfy: clarity precision unconditionality  A → common trap B/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which statement about direct effect of directives is correct?", "options": ["They always have horizontal direct effect", "They never have direct effect", "They can have vertical direct effect after the deadline if not implemented", "They apply directly to individuals in all cases"], "correctAnswer": "They can have vertical direct effect after the deadline if not implemented", "explanation": "Directives: only vertical only after deadline only if not properly implemented Very examinable  A → false B → too absolute D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Why do directives NOT have horizontal direct effect?", "options": ["They are not binding", "They only bind Member States, not individuals", "They are unclear", "They are optional"], "correctAnswer": "They only bind Member States, not individuals", "explanation": "Directives bind Member States only Therefore:→ no horizontal direct effect  A → they ARE binding C/D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "What is the duty of consistent interpretation?", "options": ["National courts must ignore EU law", "National law must be interpreted in light of EU law", "EU law must follow national law", "Courts must always apply directives directly"], "correctAnswer": "National law must be interpreted in light of EU law", "explanation": "Courts must interpret national law:→ in light of EU law (even without direct effect) Very important workaround  A/C/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which condition is required for primacy to operate effectively?", "options": ["Subsidiarity", "Direct effect of the EU rule", "National approval", "Treaty amendment"], "correctAnswer": "Direct effect of the EU rule", "explanation": "Primacy needs:➡ EU law to be applied directly Without direct effect → primacy meaningless  A/C/D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Which case established primacy of EU law?", "options": ["Van Gend en Loos", "Mangold", "Costa v ENEL", "Simmenthal"], "correctAnswer": "Costa v ENEL", "explanation": "Costa v ENEL established primacy  A → direct effect B → different doctrine D → later refinement"}, {"question": "What is the relationship between primacy and direct effect?", "options": ["Primacy exists independently", "Direct effect is irrelevant", "Primacy requires direct effect to be operational", "They contradict each other"], "correctAnswer": "Primacy requires direct effect to be operational", "explanation": "Logic: direct effect → allows application primacy → ensures priority They are interdependent  A/B/D → incorrect"}], "hard": [{"question": "A provision of EU law is directly applicable but unclear and conditional. What is the correct conclusion?", "options": ["It has direct effect", "It cannot be invoked before courts directly", "It overrides national law automatically", "It becomes a directive"], "correctAnswer": "It cannot be invoked before courts directly", "explanation": "Direct applicability ≠ direct effect If not clear/precise/unconditional:→ cannot be invoked directly  A → wrong C → requires direct effect D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "An individual invokes a directive against another private party after the deadline. What is the correct legal position?", "options": ["Allowed due to direct applicability", "Allowed due to primacy", "Not allowed (no horizontal direct effect)", "Always allowed"], "correctAnswer": "Not allowed (no horizontal direct effect)", "explanation": "Directives: NO horizontal direct effect Even after deadline  A → confusion with applicability B → primacy cannot create horizontal effect D → false"}, {"question": "Which mechanism allows individuals to benefit from directives despite lack of horizontal direct effect?", "options": ["Direct applicability", "Primacy", "Consistent interpretation of national law", "Subsidiarity"], "correctAnswer": "Consistent interpretation of national law", "explanation": "Solution:➡ consistent interpretation Courts “bend” national law to align with directive  A/B/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which statement best reflects the reasoning in Van Gend en Loos?", "options": ["EU law only binds states", "EU law creates rights for individuals enforceable in national courts", "EU law requires national implementation", "EU law is identical to international law"], "correctAnswer": "EU law creates rights for individuals enforceable in national courts", "explanation": "Van Gend en Loos: EU law creates individual rights enforceable before national courts  A → too narrow C/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Why is primacy essential for EU law?", "options": ["It increases flexibility", "It ensures uniform application of EU law across Member States", "It limits EU competences", "It replaces national law entirely"], "correctAnswer": "It ensures uniform application of EU law across Member States", "explanation": "Primacy ensures:➡ uniform application of EU law Without it → fragmentation  A/C/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which scenario best illustrates vertical direct effect?", "options": ["Individual vs individual", "Individual vs Member State authority", "State vs state", "Institution vs individual"], "correctAnswer": "Individual vs Member State authority", "explanation": "Vertical direct effect = individual vs state  A → horizontal C/D → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Which statement best reflects the relationship between direct effect and effectiveness (effet utile)?", "options": ["Direct effect limits EU law", "Direct effect ensures EU law is effective in practice", "Effectiveness replaces direct effect", "They are unrelated"], "correctAnswer": "Direct effect ensures EU law is effective in practice", "explanation": "Direct effect = tool for effectiveness (effet utile) Makes EU law practical  A/C/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "A national court faces a conflict between EU law (with direct effect) and national law. What must it do?", "options": ["Apply national law", "Refer automatically to CJEU", "Disapply national law and apply EU law", "Wait for legislation"], "correctAnswer": "Disapply national law and apply EU law", "explanation": "Court must:➡ disapply conflicting national law Strong exam point  A → violates primacy B → not always required D → wrong"}, {"question": "Which situation demonstrates failure of primacy?", "options": ["National court applies EU law", "National law overrides EU law in conflict", "EU law is applied consistently", "Directive is interpreted broadly"], "correctAnswer": "National law overrides EU law in conflict", "explanation": "Primacy fails if:➡ national law overrides EU law That’s the core violation  A/C/D → correct applications"}, {"question": "Which statement best reflects the combined effect of autonomy, direct effect, and primacy?", "options": ["EU law is dependent on national law", "EU law operates as an independent and superior legal order within its scope", "EU law is optional", "EU law only binds institutions"], "correctAnswer": "EU law operates as an independent and superior legal order within its scope", "explanation": "Combined effect: autonomy → independent system direct effect → enforceability primacy → superiority Together = functional EU legal order  A/C/D → incorrect"}]}}, {"id": "topic5", "title": "Judicial Protection in the European Union", "notesHtml": "<div class=\"notes-block\">\n<h3>1. Structure of the Court of Justice of the European Union</h3>\n<p>The Court of Justice of the European Union consists of:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the Court of Justice (CJEU)</li>\n<li>the General Court</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The special feature of the CJEU is that it has many procedures. This can be explained by the supranational nature of the EU: a high level of power has been conferred to the EU by the Member States in the Treaties, which entails extensive powers of the CJEU to ensure that, in the interpretation and application of the Treaties, EU law is observed.</p>\n<p>There are three main types of procedures that can be brought before the CJEU:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>actions against EU institutions</li>\n<li>actions against Member States</li>\n<li>questions from national courts (preliminary rulings)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>2. Actions Against EU Institutions</h3>\n<p>Actions against EU institutions include:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>actions for annulment (Article 263 TFEU)</li>\n<li>actions for failure to act (Article 265 TFEU)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>These actions are generally brought by non-privileged applicants (such as citizens or companies) before the General Court as the first instance.</p>\n<p>According to Article 256(1) TFEU, the General Court is the court of first instance for these types of actions. Decisions of the General Court can be appealed to the Court of Justice, but only on points of law, meaning only where there has been an error in the interpretation or application of the law.</p>\n<h3>3. Actions Against Member States (Infringement Procedures)</h3>\n<p>Actions against Member States are infringement procedures under:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Article 258 TFEU (Commission against Member State)</li>\n<li>Article 259 TFEU (Member State against another Member State)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>These cases are always handled by the Court of Justice of the European Union.</p>\n<h3>4. Preliminary Rulings (Questions from National Courts)</h3>\n<p>Preliminary rulings arise when a national court is confronted with a question of EU law and is unsure about its interpretation or validity. The national court refers the question to the CJEU.</p>\n<p>Originally, preliminary rulings were handled only by the Court of Justice. However, according to Article 256(3) TFEU, the General Court can also deal with certain preliminary rulings in specific areas listed in the Statute.</p>\n<p>Two important safeguards exist:</p>\n<p>if a case may affect the unity or consistency of EU law, the General Court must refer it to the Court of Justice</p>\n<p>if there is a serious risk to the unity and consistency of EU law, the Court of Justice may review the decision of the General Court</p>\n<p>Judicial protection in the EU does not consist only of procedures before the CJEU; national courts also play an important role.</p>\n<h3>5. Article 263 TFEU: Actions for Annulment</h3>\n<p>An action for annulment allows the Court to review the legality of acts of EU institutions.</p>\n<p>If successful, the act is declared void under Article 264 TFEU.</p>\n<h4>5.1 Conditions for Annulment</h4>\n<p>Only acts intended to produce legal effects for third parties can be challenged.</p>\n<p>The Court of Justice determines whether an act produces such effects. This was clarified in the ERTA judgment, where the Court adopted a broad interpretation and did not restrict actions for annulment only to regulations, directives, and decisions. It recognised that other acts may also have binding legal effects.</p>\n<h4>5.2 Claimants in Actions for Annulment</h4>\n<p>There are three categories of claimants:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Privileged claimants:</li>\n<li>Member States</li>\n<li>European Parliament</li>\n<li>European Commission</li>\n<li>Council of the European Union</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>These do not need to demonstrate any specific interest; they may bring an action simply because they consider the act unlawful.</p>\n<p>Semi-privileged claimants:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Court of Auditors</li>\n<li>European Central Bank</li>\n<li>Committee of the Regions</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>These may act only to protect their prerogatives.</p>\n<p>Non-privileged claimants (natural and legal persons):</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>may bring an action when they are the addressee of the act</li>\n<li>if not the addressee, they must show that the act is of direct and individual concern</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>This third category has very limited possibilities to bring an action.</p>\n<h4>5.3 Grounds for Annulment</h4>\n<p>An act may be annulled on several grounds:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>lack of competence</li>\n<li>infringement of an essential procedural requirement</li>\n<li>infringement of the Treaties or of any rule of law relating to their application</li>\n<li>misuse of powers (détournement de pouvoir)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The legality of an act depends on compliance with higher-ranking norms in the hierarchy of EU law. For example, secondary legislation must comply with:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the Treaties</li>\n<li>general principles of EU law</li>\n<li>international agreements concluded by the EU</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>This reflects the hierarchical structure of EU law and is central to legality review.</p>\n<h3>6. Article 265 TFEU: Action for Failure to Act</h3>\n<p>An action for failure to act applies when an EU institution fails to act where it is required to do so.</p>\n<p>Before bringing the action, the institution must first be called upon to act.</p>\n<p>If the institution:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>gives a negative answer, this may be challenged through an annulment action under Article 263 TFEU</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>gives no answer within two months, the applicant has another two months to bring an action under Article 265 TFEU</p>\n<p>There are relatively few successful cases, often because:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the obligation to act is not sufficiently specific</li>\n<li>or the institution takes action before the case is decided</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>7. Infringement Procedures Against Member States</h3>\n<p>Infringement procedures are brought when a Member State fails to fulfil its obligations under EU law.</p>\n<h4>7.1 Article 258 TFEU: Commission Against Member State</h4>\n<p>The European Commission may initiate an infringement procedure. It has discretion over whether to bring the case before the Court.</p>\n<p>The procedure begins with a pre-contentious phase:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>enquiry</li>\n<li>formal notice</li>\n<li>reasoned opinion</li>\n<li>The reasoned opinion defines:</li>\n<li>the nature of the breach</li>\n<li>possible remedies</li>\n<li>the period for compliance</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>If the issue is not resolved, the case proceeds to the contentious phase before the Court of Justice.</p>\n<h4>7.2 Article 259 TFEU: Member State Against Member State</h4>\n<p>A Member State may also bring an infringement action against another Member State.</p>\n<p>In this case:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the Commission must first be alerted</li>\n<li>the Commission conducts the pre-contentious phase</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>However, unlike Article 258, the Commission does not control whether the case proceeds to the Court. Even if the Commission decides not to proceed, the Member State may still bring the case.</p>\n<h4>7.3 Article 260 TFEU: Penalties</h4>\n<p>If a Member State fails to comply with a judgment, the Court may impose:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>lump sum payments</li>\n<li>penalty payments</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>This reflects the strong supranational nature of EU law, which goes beyond what is found in public international law systems such as the ICJ.</p>\n<h3>8. Preliminary Rulings (Article 267 TFEU)</h3>\n<p>Preliminary rulings arise when national courts require clarification of EU law in order to decide a case.</p>\n<p>They may concern:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>interpretation of EU law</li>\n<li>validity of EU acts</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The Court of Justice is the only body that can declare EU secondary legislation invalid.</p>\n<h4>8.1 Obligation to Refer</h4>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>lower courts may refer</li>\n<li>courts of last instance must refer</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>If a final court fails to refer and decides contrary to EU law, this cannot be appealed to the CJEU.</p>\n<h4>8.2 Case Law: CJEU, Mangold (Preliminary Ruling Admissibility)</h4>\n<p>In Case C-144/04, Mangold, the Court clarified the conditions for admissibility of preliminary rulings.</p>\n<p>The Court examines whether:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the question is necessary for the national court to decide the case</li>\n<li>the request concerns a real legal issue and not a hypothetical one</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>Although the CJEU generally trusts national courts, it retains the final authority to determine admissibility.</p>\n<h3>9. Role of National Courts in EU Judicial Protection</h3>\n<p>National courts are the principal enforcers of EU law, as recognised in the Van Gend en Loos judgment.</p>\n<p>They must ensure the effectiveness of EU law by:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>applying the principle of primacy</li>\n<li>using consistent interpretation</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>If consistent interpretation is not possible, national courts must disapply conflicting national law, provided the EU rule has direct effect (clear, precise, and unconditional).</p>\n<p>This makes national courts part of the European judicial system.</p>\n<h3>10. National Procedural Autonomy and Its Limits</h3>\n<p>Member States have national procedural autonomy. However, according to Article 19(1) TEU, they must provide remedies sufficient to ensure effective legal protection in areas covered by EU law.</p>\n<p>The CJEU has developed two key principles:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Principle of equivalence: EU law must not be treated less favourably than similar national law</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>Principle of effectiveness: national procedural rules must not make the exercise of EU rights impossible in practice</p>\n<h3>11. Division of Labour Between National Courts and the CJEU</h3>\n<p>When a national court refers a question to the CJEU:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the national proceedings are suspended</li>\n<li>the CJEU provides an interpretation or validity ruling</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The CJEU does not decide the national case. It only provides guidance. The national court then applies that interpretation to the case.</p>\n<p>There is no appeal from national courts to the CJEU.</p>\n<p>If a final national court fails to request a preliminary ruling and decides contrary to EU law, the only remedy is:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>an infringement procedure initiated by the Commission or another Member State</li>\n</ul></div>\n</div>", "quizData": {"easy": [{"question": "What bodies make up the Court of Justice of the EU?", "options": ["European Council and Commission", "Parliament and ECB", "CJEU and General Court", "National courts"], "correctAnswer": "CJEU and General Court", "explanation": "The EU judicial system consists of the Court of Justice and the General Court. Others are political or national bodies."}, {"question": "Which article governs actions for annulment?", "options": ["Article 263 TFEU", "Article 258 TFEU", "Article 267 TFEU", "Article 265 TFEU"], "correctAnswer": "Article 263 TFEU", "explanation": "263 = annulment. 258 = infringement, 267 = preliminary rulings, 265 = failure to act."}, {"question": "If an annulment action is successful, what happens?", "options": ["The act is reviewed", "The act is declared void", "The act is amended", "The act is suspended"], "correctAnswer": "The act is declared void", "explanation": "Article 264 TFEU: act becomes void. Others are not provided for in EU law."}, {"question": "Who hears actions brought by non-privileged applicants first?", "options": ["CJEU", "National courts", "European Parliament", "General Court"], "correctAnswer": "General Court", "explanation": "General Court = first instance (Art 256). Others have no such role."}, {"question": "Which procedure concerns Member States failing EU obligations?", "options": ["Infringement procedure", "Annulment action", "Preliminary ruling", "Failure to act"], "correctAnswer": "Infringement procedure", "explanation": "Infringement = against Member States. Others concern institutions or interpretation."}, {"question": "Which article governs preliminary rulings?", "options": ["Article 256", "Article 263", "Article 267", "Article 259"], "correctAnswer": "Article 267", "explanation": "267 = preliminary rulings. Others deal with jurisdiction, annulment, or MS disputes."}, {"question": "Which institution can bring infringement proceedings under Article 258?", "options": ["Council", "Commission", "ECB", "Parliament"], "correctAnswer": "Commission", "explanation": "Commission has discretion under 258. Others cannot initiate this procedure."}, {"question": "What is required for annulment actions?", "options": ["Financial loss", "National approval", "Legal effect for third parties", "Political interest"], "correctAnswer": "Legal effect for third parties", "explanation": "Only acts producing legal effects are reviewable (ERTA). Others are irrelevant."}, {"question": "What is the time limit for annulment actions?", "options": ["1 year", "6 months", "No limit", "2 months"], "correctAnswer": "2 months", "explanation": "Strict 2-month limit. Others are incorrect."}, {"question": "Which courts primarily enforce EU law?", "options": ["General Court", "National courts", "CJEU", "Commission"], "correctAnswer": "National courts", "explanation": "National courts = primary enforcers (Van Gend & Loos). Others play supporting roles."}], "medium": [{"question": "Appeals from the General Court to the CJEU are limited to:", "options": ["Law only", "Facts only", "Both law and facts", "Political reasoning"], "correctAnswer": "Law only", "explanation": "Appeals only on points of law. Facts cannot be reassessed."}, {"question": "Which claimants do NOT need to show interest?", "options": ["Companies", "NGOs", "Natural persons", "Privileged applicants"], "correctAnswer": "Privileged applicants", "explanation": "Privileged applicants act to protect legality. Others must prove concern."}, {"question": "Non-privileged applicants must demonstrate:", "options": ["Nationality", "Economic damage", "Direct and individual concern", "Political relevance"], "correctAnswer": "Direct and individual concern", "explanation": "Core admissibility requirement. Others are not legal criteria."}, {"question": "Under Article 265, before bringing action you must:", "options": ["Appeal to CJEU", "Call on institution to act", "Notify Parliament", "Start infringement procedure"], "correctAnswer": "Call on institution to act", "explanation": "Mandatory procedural step. Others are incorrect processes."}, {"question": "If no reply is given under Article 265:", "options": ["Immediate action possible", "No action allowed", "2 months wait + 2 months to act", "1 year delay required"], "correctAnswer": "2 months wait + 2 months to act", "explanation": "Specific timeline rule. Others contradict treaty procedure."}, {"question": "ERTA judgment established that:", "options": ["Only directives are reviewable", "Only regulations matter", "Only decisions count", "All acts with legal effects are reviewable"], "correctAnswer": "All acts with legal effects are reviewable", "explanation": "Broad interpretation. Others are overly restrictive."}, {"question": "Which defines the scope of infringement proceedings?", "options": ["Formal notice", "Treaty provisions", "Reasoned opinion", "Judgment"], "correctAnswer": "Reasoned opinion", "explanation": "Reasoned opinion fixes scope. Others are preparatory or final steps."}, {"question": "Under Article 259, Member States must first:", "options": ["Go directly to CJEU", "Alert the Commission", "Contact Parliament", "Seek national approval"], "correctAnswer": "Alert the Commission", "explanation": "Mandatory pre-step. Others are not required."}, {"question": "What ensures uniform application of EU law?", "options": ["Commission enforcement", "National courts", "Preliminary rulings", "Council decisions"], "correctAnswer": "Preliminary rulings", "explanation": "Preliminary rulings guarantee uniform interpretation."}, {"question": "Which principle requires equal treatment of EU and national claims?", "options": ["Primacy", "Direct effect", "Effectiveness", "Equivalence"], "correctAnswer": "Equivalence", "explanation": "Equivalence = no discrimination. Effectiveness = practical enforceability."}], "hard": [{"question": "Why does the CJEU have extensive powers?", "options": ["Judicial activism", "Treaty-based power conferral", "Political pressure", "Institutional competition"], "correctAnswer": "Treaty-based power conferral", "explanation": "Powers derive from treaties. Others are speculative or incorrect."}, {"question": "Why are non-privileged applicants limited?", "options": ["Political compromise", "Institutional balance protection", "Treaty silence", "Economic efficiency"], "correctAnswer": "Institutional balance protection", "explanation": "Limits prevent excessive challenges and protect institutional structure."}, {"question": "What is the function of Article 264 TFEU?", "options": ["Starts procedure", "Defines jurisdiction", "Declares act void", "Imposes sanctions"], "correctAnswer": "Declares act void", "explanation": "Provides consequence of annulment. Others relate to different provisions."}, {"question": "Why is the reasoned opinion crucial?", "options": ["Ends the procedure", "Defines scope of the case", "Imposes penalties", "Binds the Court"], "correctAnswer": "Defines scope of the case", "explanation": "It limits what can be argued later. Others misstate its function."}, {"question": "Why can the CJEU refuse a preliminary ruling (Mangold)?", "options": ["Political sensitivity", "Lack of jurisdiction", "Question is hypothetical or irrelevant", "National conflict"], "correctAnswer": "Question is hypothetical or irrelevant", "explanation": "Court avoids advisory opinions. Others are incorrect."}, {"question": "What best reflects EU supranationalism?", "options": ["Direct effect", "National autonomy", "Subsidiarity", "Article 260 penalties"], "correctAnswer": "Article 260 penalties", "explanation": "Financial penalties show strong enforcement power."}, {"question": "Why must last instance courts refer questions?", "options": ["Efficiency", "Political obligation", "Cooperation", "Ensure uniformity of EU law"], "correctAnswer": "Ensure uniformity of EU law", "explanation": "Prevents divergent interpretations."}, {"question": "What happens if a last instance court fails to refer?", "options": ["Case reopens", "Automatic annulment", "Infringement procedure against the state", "Appeal to CJEU"], "correctAnswer": "Infringement procedure against the state", "explanation": "No direct appeal exists → enforcement via infringement."}, {"question": "What is the relationship between CJEU and national courts?", "options": ["Hierarchical", "Competitive", "Independent", "Cooperative division of labour"], "correctAnswer": "Cooperative division of labour", "explanation": "CJEU interprets, national courts apply."}, {"question": "Why can individuals NOT appeal national decisions to the CJEU?", "options": ["Treaty prohibition", "Institutional design of the system", "Lack of jurisdiction", "Political reasons"], "correctAnswer": "Institutional design of the system", "explanation": "System relies on preliminary rulings, not appeals."}]}}, {"id": "topic6", "title": "EU Institutions and Distribution of Powers", "notesHtml": "<div class=\"notes-block\">\n<h3>1. EU Institutional Framework</h3>\n<p>Questions of objectives and effectiveness are related to the attribution of certain functions to international organisations. This is explained through the concept of functionalism (as seen in the Reparations for Injuries case) and the principle of speciality (as in the WHO advisory opinion) in public international law.</p>\n<p>This also relates to principal–agent theory, according to which states (principals) create international organisations (agents) and confer powers upon them to fulfil specific functions. However, the legal personality of these organisations is limited to the extent necessary to effectively discharge the objectives conferred upon them by Member States.</p>\n<p>In the case of the EU, according to Article 13(1) and (2) TEU, each EU institution has been given objectives and has been conferred limited powers in the Treaties sufficient to attain those objectives effectively. This is what maintains institutional balance within the EU.</p>\n<h3>2. General Characteristics of EU Institutions</h3>\n<p>The EU institutional framework reflects both intergovernmental and supranational elements.</p>\n<p>Typical for intergovernmental organisations are institutions composed of representatives of the executives of Member States, such as:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the European Council</li>\n<li>the Council of the European Union</li>\n<li>At the same time, the EU also has supranational characteristics, such as:</li>\n<li>the Court of Justice of the European Union, which has a wide range of procedures and powers</li>\n<li>the European Parliament, which is directly elected and reflects a high degree of integration</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>the European Commission, which represents the interests of the Union as a whole and is considered supranational par excellence</p>\n<h3>3. European Parliament (Article 14 TEU)</h3>\n<p>According to Article 14(1) TEU, the European Parliament has four main functions:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>legislative and budgetary functions, exercised together with the Council (co-decision procedure)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>oversight function (political control), including the ability to adopt a motion of censure against the Commission (Article 17(8) TEU), which would require the Commission to resign as a body</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>advisory functions, particularly in relation to treaties</li>\n<li>appointment functions, including the election of the President of the Commission</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h4>3.1 Composition of the European Parliament</h4>\n<p>According to Article 14(2) and (3) TEU, Members of the European Parliament are:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>directly elected by EU citizens</li>\n<li>elected for a five-year term</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>allocated according to degressive proportionality (minimum 6 and maximum 96 members per Member State)</p>\n<p>Members are not grouped by nationality, but by political ideology (political groups).</p>\n<p>Most of the daily work is carried out in specialised committees, such as:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>foreign affairs</li>\n<li>economic and monetary affairs</li>\n<li>civil liberties, justice and home affairs</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The European Parliament is officially located in Strasbourg, although most work is conducted in Brussels.</p>\n<h4>3.2 Decision-Making in the European Parliament</h4>\n<p>Decisions are generally taken by simple majority with a quorum of one-third.</p>\n<p>In certain cases, a special majority with a quorum of two-thirds is required, for example in procedures relating to serious breaches under Article 7 TEU.</p>\n<h3>4. European Council (Article 15 TEU)</h3>\n<p>The European Council provides the general political direction and priorities of the EU.</p>\n<p>It does not have legislative power, except where the Treaties explicitly provide otherwise. It also has certain organic functions, such as appointing members of the Commission.</p>\n<h4>4.1 Composition of the European Council</h4>\n<p>According to Article 15(2) TEU, the European Council is composed of:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Heads of State or Government of the Member States</li>\n<li>the President of the European Council</li>\n<li>the President of the Commission</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The High Representative of the Union also takes part.</p>\n<h4>4.2 Meetings and Decision-Making</h4>\n<p>According to Article 15(3) TEU, the European Council meets twice every six months.</p>\n<p>According to Article 15(4) TEU, decisions are generally taken by consensus, unless the Treaties provide otherwise.</p>\n<p>Examples include:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>unanimity for decisions under Article 7 TEU</li>\n<li>qualified majority for certain institutional decisions</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h4>4.3 President of the European Council</h4>\n<p>According to Article 15(5) TEU, the President of the European Council is elected for a term of two and a half years.</p>\n<p>According to Article 15(6) TEU, the President:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>sets the agenda</li>\n<li>facilitates consensus among members</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>5. Council of the European Union (Article 16 TEU)</h3>\n<p>According to Article 16(1) TEU, the Council has:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>legislative functions (together with the Parliament)</li>\n<li>policy-making and coordinating functions</li>\n<li>some executive functions (for example in external actions)</li>\n<li>organic functions</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h4>5.1 Composition and Organisation</h4>\n<p>According to Article 16(2) TEU, the Council is composed of representatives of Member States at ministerial level.</p>\n<p>According to Article 16(6) TEU, the Council meets in different configurations depending on the topic (for example, general affairs or foreign affairs).</p>\n<p>According to Article 16(9) TEU, the presidency rotates every six months between Member States.</p>\n<h4>5.2 Decision-Making in the Council</h4>\n<p>According to Article 16(3) TEU, decisions are generally taken by qualified majority.</p>\n<p>According to Article 16(4) TEU, qualified majority means:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>55% of Member States (minimum 15 states)</li>\n<li>representing at least 65% of the EU population</li>\n<li>Decisions may also be taken by:</li>\n<li>simple majority (for procedural matters)</li>\n<li>unanimity (for example, accession to the EU)</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>6. European Commission (Article 17 TEU)</h3>\n<h4>6.1 Composition and Appointment</h4>\n<p>According to Article 17(4) TEU, each Member State may nominate one Commissioner.</p>\n<p>Although Article 17(5) TEU provides that only two-thirds of Member States should be represented, this has not been implemented in practice, as the European Council can unanimously decide otherwise.</p>\n<p>The appointment process (Article 17(7) TEU) consists of:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>nomination of the President of the Commission by the European Council</li>\n<li>approval by the European Parliament</li>\n<li>nomination of Commissioners by Member States</li>\n<li>adoption of the list by the Council together with the President</li>\n<li>approval of the entire Commission by the European Parliament</li>\n<li>formal appointment by the European Council</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h4>6.2 Independence and Responsibility</h4>\n<p>According to Article 17(3) TEU, the Commission is independent from national governments and institutions.</p>\n<p>However, according to Article 17(8) TEU, it is politically responsible to the European Parliament, which may adopt a motion of censure leading to the resignation of the entire Commission.</p>\n<h4>6.3 Functions of the Commission</h4>\n<p>According to Article 17(1) and (2) TEU, the Commission:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>promotes the general interests of the Union</li>\n<li>has the exclusive right of legislative initiative</li>\n<li>ensures compliance with EU law (infringement procedures)</li>\n<li>implements EU legislation</li>\n<li>manages the EU budget</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h4>6.4 Decision-Making in the Commission</h4>\n<p>Decisions are generally taken by consensus, but when a vote is required, a simple majority is sufficient.</p>\n<p>The Commission is organised into Directorates-General, which deal with specific policy areas, as well as horizontal services such as legal services.</p>\n<h3>7. Court of Justice of the European Union (Article 19 TEU)</h3>\n<p>The CJEU ensures the interpretation and application of EU law.</p>\n<p>It consists of:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>the Court of Justice (final or only instance)</li>\n<li>the General Court (first instance)</li>\n<li>Each Member State appoints:</li>\n<li>one judge to the Court of Justice</li>\n<li>two judges to the General Court</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>There are also Advocates General (currently 11), who provide independent opinions.</p>\n<p>Judges are appointed by common agreement of Member States, following an assessment of:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>independence</li>\n<li>ability to deal with EU law</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>8. Other EU Institutions and Bodies</h3>\n<p>Other important bodies include:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>European Central Bank</li>\n<li>Court of Auditors</li>\n<li>European Ombudsperson</li>\n<li>European Data Protection Supervisor</li>\n<li>European Economic and Social Committee</li>\n<li>Committee of the Regions</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h3>9. Legislative Power and Procedures</h3>\n<p>The EU legislative process consists of several phases.</p>\n<h4>9.1 Proposal Stage</h4>\n<p>The Commission proposes legislation (Article 17(2) TEU).</p>\n<p>Other institutions may request proposals, but this is not binding. The Commission may also withdraw its proposal if amendments undermine its objectives.</p>\n<h4>9.2 Subsidiarity Check</h4>\n<p>National parliaments review whether the proposal complies with subsidiarity.</p>\n<p>If one-third of national parliaments object, a yellow card procedure is triggered, requiring reconsideration of the proposal.</p>\n<h4>9.3 Ordinary Legislative Procedure</h4>\n<p>The European Parliament and the Council act as co-legislators.</p>\n<p>The proposal goes through several readings, with possible amendments until both institutions agree on the same text.</p>\n<p>In practice, agreement is often reached earlier through informal trilogue negotiations.</p>\n<h4>9.4 Special Legislative Procedures</h4>\n<p>Two main forms exist:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>Consent procedure: Parliament may only approve or reject</li>\n<li>Consultation procedure: Parliament gives a non-binding opinion</li>\n</ul></div>\n<h4>9.5 Adoption and Publication</h4>\n<p>After agreement, the act is signed by the Presidents of the Parliament and the Council and published in the Official Journal, after which it becomes binding.</p>\n<h3>10. Executive Power in the EU</h3>\n<p>The Commission holds most executive powers:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>implementation of legislation</li>\n<li>management of the budget</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The Council also exercises executive powers in specific areas, such as foreign policy.</p>\n<p>Member States play a key role in implementation through indirect administration, subject to the principles of equivalence and effectiveness.</p>\n<h3>11. Oversight and Judicial Protection</h3>\n<p>Judicial protection is mainly carried out by the CJEU through:</p>\n<div class=\"mini-card\"><ul>\n<li>annulment actions</li>\n<li>failure to act procedures</li>\n<li>infringement procedures</li>\n<li>preliminary rulings</li>\n<li>National courts also contribute through:</li>\n<li>direct effect</li>\n<li>primacy</li>\n<li>preliminary rulings</li>\n<li>Oversight is exercised by:</li>\n<li>the Commission (monitoring compliance)</li>\n<li>Member States (infringement procedures)</li>\n<li>the European Parliament (political control, including motion of censure)</li>\n</ul></div>\n</div>", "quizData": {"easy": [{"question": "Which principle ensures that each EU institution acts within its assigned powers?", "options": ["Institutional balance", "Subsidiarity", "Proportionality", "Sincere cooperation"], "correctAnswer": "Institutional balance", "explanation": "Ensures each institution acts within Treaty limits  B/C → govern use of competences, not institutional roles D → concerns Member States’ duties"}, {"question": "Which institution is directly elected by EU citizens?", "options": ["European Commission", "European Parliament", "European Council", "Council of the EU"], "correctAnswer": "European Parliament", "explanation": "Only EU institution directly elected by citizens  A/C/D → composed of representatives or appointed"}, {"question": "Which institution provides general political direction but has no legislative function?", "options": ["Council of the EU", "European Commission", "European Council", "CJEU"], "correctAnswer": "European Council", "explanation": "Sets general political direction, no legislative role  A → co-legislator B → executive/initiative D → judicial"}, {"question": "Which institution has the exclusive right of legislative initiative?", "options": ["European Commission", "European Parliament", "Council of the EU", "European Council"], "correctAnswer": "European Commission", "explanation": "Holds monopoly of legislative initiative  B/C/D → can request but not propose"}, {"question": "Which institution represents Member States at ministerial level?", "options": ["European Parliament", "European Council", "Council of the EU", "Commission"], "correctAnswer": "Council of the EU", "explanation": "Ministers represent Member States  B → heads of state (European Council) A/D → not MS representation"}, {"question": "What is the main role of the CJEU?", "options": ["Budget control", "Judicial review and interpretation of EU law", "Legislative function", "Policy-making"], "correctAnswer": "Judicial review and interpretation of EU law", "explanation": "Ensures interpretation + judicial review of EU law  C/D → political functions A → irrelevant"}, {"question": "Which institution can adopt a motion of censure?", "options": ["Council", "European Parliament", "Commission", "European Council"], "correctAnswer": "European Parliament", "explanation": "Can adopt motion of censure → Commission resigns  others → no such power"}, {"question": "What is the baseline decision-making rule in the Council?", "options": ["Qualified majority voting", "Consensus", "Unanimity", "Simple majority"], "correctAnswer": "Qualified majority voting", "explanation": "Default rule in Council decision-making  B/C → exceptions D → rare procedural cases"}, {"question": "Which institution is supranational par excellence?", "options": ["European Council", "Council", "European Parliament", "European Commission"], "correctAnswer": "European Commission", "explanation": "Acts in EU interest, independent from MS  others → intergovernmental elements"}, {"question": "Which institution ensures compliance with EU law by Member States?", "options": ["European Parliament", "Council", "European Council", "European Commission"], "correctAnswer": "European Commission", "explanation": "Oversees MS compliance → infringement procedures  others → political/legislative roles"}], "medium": [{"question": "Which combination reflects legislative power?", "options": ["Parliament + Council of the EU", "Commission + Council", "European Council + Parliament", "Commission + CJEU"], "correctAnswer": "Parliament + Council of the EU", "explanation": "Legislative power = co-decision  others → incomplete combinations"}, {"question": "Which statement best describes the ordinary legislative procedure?", "options": ["Commission decides alone", "Council dominates", "Parliament and Council must agree on identical text", "Parliament approves only"], "correctAnswer": "Parliament and Council must agree on identical text", "explanation": "Ordinary procedure requires agreement on identical text  A/B/D → incorrect roles"}, {"question": "What is the yellow card mechanism?", "options": ["EP veto", "National parliaments trigger reconsideration of proposal", "Commission sanction", "Court decision"], "correctAnswer": "National parliaments trigger reconsideration of proposal", "explanation": "National parliaments trigger subsidiarity review  A → EP does not veto like this C/D → incorrect"}, {"question": "Which statement about the Commission is correct?", "options": ["It represents Member States", "It is directly elected", "It has no executive power", "It acts independently in EU interest"], "correctAnswer": "It acts independently in EU interest", "explanation": "Commission acts in EU interest, not MS interest  A → Council role B → EP C → false"}, {"question": "Which institution has rotating presidency?", "options": ["European Council", "European Parliament", "Commission", "Council of the EU"], "correctAnswer": "Council of the EU", "explanation": "Rotating presidency every 6 months  others → fixed or different structure"}, {"question": "European Council decision-making is primarily:", "options": ["Simple majority", "Qualified majority", "Consensus", "Unanimity always"], "correctAnswer": "Consensus", "explanation": "European Council = consensus-based  A/B → Council rules D → only in specific cases"}, {"question": "Which is part of special legislative procedure?", "options": ["Co-decision", "Consultation procedure", "Trilogues", "Preliminary ruling"], "correctAnswer": "Consultation procedure", "explanation": "Special procedure = Council dominates  A → ordinary procedure C/D → not procedures"}, {"question": "Which institution primarily exercises executive power?", "options": ["Council", "European Council", "European Commission", "Parliament"], "correctAnswer": "European Commission", "explanation": "Main executive authority  A/B/D → partial or incorrect"}, {"question": "Which statement about CJEU is correct?", "options": ["No hierarchy", "General Court is first instance, CJEU higher level", "Only one court exists", "National courts replace it"], "correctAnswer": "General Court is first instance, CJEU higher level", "explanation": "General Court (first instance), CJEU (higher level)  others → wrong structure"}, {"question": "Which principle governs national enforcement of EU law?", "options": ["Primacy", "Direct effect", "Subsidiarity", "Equivalence and effectiveness"], "correctAnswer": "Equivalence and effectiveness", "explanation": "Governs MS enforcement of EU law  A/B → different doctrines C → competence issue"}], "hard": [{"question": "A legislative proposal is requested but not introduced. Why?", "options": ["Parliament blocks it", "Council refuses", "Commission retains discretion over initiative", "CJEU intervenes"], "correctAnswer": "Commission retains discretion over initiative", "explanation": "Commission is not bound by requests  A/B → no such authority D → no role here"}, {"question": "Which scenario breaches institutional balance?", "options": ["Commission proposes legislation", "Parliament adopts budget", "Council exceeds Treaty powers", "CJEU interprets law"], "correctAnswer": "Council exceeds Treaty powers", "explanation": "Breach = acting outside Treaty limits  others → lawful actions"}, {"question": "What best describes a trilogue?", "options": ["Judicial process", "Informal negotiation to reach agreement early", "Treaty rule", "National procedure"], "correctAnswer": "Informal negotiation to reach agreement early", "explanation": "Informal negotiation to avoid multiple readings  A/C/D → incorrect classification"}, {"question": "Parliament can only approve/reject a measure. Which procedure?", "options": ["Ordinary", "Consultation", "Delegated act", "Consent procedure"], "correctAnswer": "Consent procedure", "explanation": "EP = yes/no only, no amendments  B → EP gives opinion only A → full co-decision"}, {"question": "Which scenario shows indirect administration?", "options": ["Commission enforces directly", "CJEU applies law", "Member States implement EU law under EU constraints", "Parliament supervises"], "correctAnswer": "Member States implement EU law under EU constraints", "explanation": "MS implement EU law under EU constraints  A → direct administration B/D → different roles"}, {"question": "Qualified majority voting requires:", "options": ["Only population", "Only number of states", "Both population and number of states thresholds", "Unanimity"], "correctAnswer": "Both population and number of states thresholds", "explanation": "Requires: 55% states 65% population Dual legitimacy  A/B → incomplete D → unanimity"}, {"question": "Which institution may withdraw a proposal?", "options": ["Parliament", "Council", "European Council", "Commission"], "correctAnswer": "Commission", "explanation": "Can withdraw proposal (especially if distorted)  others → no such power"}, {"question": "Which reflects judicial protection?", "options": ["Commission initiative", "Parliament oversight", "Council voting", "CJEU annulment/infringement procedures"], "correctAnswer": "CJEU annulment/infringement procedures", "explanation": "Judicial protection: annulment infringement preliminary ruling  others → non-judicial"}, {"question": "Which scenario shows checks and balances?", "options": ["Commission acts alone", "Council dominates", "Parliament censures Commission", "CJEU legislates"], "correctAnswer": "Parliament censures Commission", "explanation": "Example of checks and balances  A/B/D → imbalance"}, {"question": "Which best reflects EU power distribution?", "options": ["Fully centralized", "Strict separation like states", "Member States control everything", "Shared powers + institutional checks"], "correctAnswer": "Shared powers + institutional checks", "explanation": "EU = hybrid system: shared powers institutional checks  A/B → too rigid C → incorrect"}]}}];

const topicSelect = document.getElementById("topicSelect");
const notesContent = document.getElementById("notesContent");
const showNotesBtn = document.getElementById("showNotesBtn");
const showQuizBtn = document.getElementById("showQuizBtn");
const notesSection = document.getElementById("notesSection");
const quizSection = document.getElementById("quizSection");

const difficultySelect = document.getElementById("difficultySelect");
const quizPlaceholder = document.getElementById("quizPlaceholder");
const quizArea = document.getElementById("quizArea");
const difficultyBadge = document.getElementById("difficultyBadge");
const questionText = document.getElementById("questionText");
const optionsContainer = document.getElementById("optionsContainer");
const submitBtn = document.getElementById("submitBtn");
const nextBtn = document.getElementById("nextBtn");
const restartBtn = document.getElementById("restartBtn");

const resultBox = document.getElementById("resultBox");
const resultMessage = document.getElementById("resultMessage");
const correctAnswerSpan = document.getElementById("correctAnswer");
const answerExplanationSpan = document.getElementById("answerExplanation");
const questionCounter = document.getElementById("questionCounter");
const scoreCounter = document.getElementById("scoreCounter");

let currentTopic = topics[0];
let currentDifficulty = "";
let currentQuestionIndex = 0;
let currentScore = 0;
let currentQuestions = [];

function fillTopicSelect() {
  topicSelect.innerHTML = "";
  topics.forEach((topic, index) => {
    const option = document.createElement("option");
    option.value = topic.id;
    option.textContent = `${index + 1}. ${topic.title}`;
    topicSelect.appendChild(option);
  });
}

function labelForDifficulty(value) {
  if (value === "easy") return "🟢 Level 1";
  if (value === "medium") return "🟡 Level 2";
  if (value === "hard") return "🔴 Level 3";
  return "";
}

function updateScore() {
  scoreCounter.textContent = currentScore;
}

function resetQuizView() {
  quizPlaceholder.classList.remove("hidden");
  quizArea.classList.add("hidden");
  resultBox.classList.add("hidden");
  nextBtn.classList.add("hidden");
  restartBtn.classList.add("hidden");
  submitBtn.disabled = false;
  questionCounter.textContent = "0 / 0";
  scoreCounter.textContent = "0";
}

function loadTopic(topicId) {
  currentTopic = topics.find(t => t.id === topicId) || topics[0];
  notesContent.innerHTML = currentTopic.notesHtml;
  difficultySelect.value = "";
  currentDifficulty = "";
  currentQuestionIndex = 0;
  currentScore = 0;
  currentQuestions = [];
  updateScore();
  resetQuizView();
}

function showCurrentQuestion() {
  const currentQuestion = currentQuestions[currentQuestionIndex];

  quizPlaceholder.classList.add("hidden");
  quizArea.classList.remove("hidden");
  resultBox.classList.add("hidden");
  resultBox.classList.remove("incorrect");
  nextBtn.classList.add("hidden");
  restartBtn.classList.remove("hidden");
  submitBtn.disabled = false;

  difficultyBadge.textContent = labelForDifficulty(currentDifficulty);
  questionText.textContent = currentQuestion.question;
  questionCounter.textContent = `${currentQuestionIndex + 1} / ${currentQuestions.length}`;
  optionsContainer.innerHTML = "";

  currentQuestion.options.forEach(option => {
    const label = document.createElement("label");
    label.classList.add("option-label");

    const radio = document.createElement("input");
    radio.type = "radio";
    radio.name = "quizOption";
    radio.value = option;

    label.appendChild(radio);
    label.appendChild(document.createTextNode(" " + option));
    optionsContainer.appendChild(label);
  });
}

showNotesBtn.addEventListener("click", () => {
  notesSection.classList.remove("hidden");
  quizSection.classList.add("hidden");
  showNotesBtn.classList.add("active");
  showQuizBtn.classList.remove("active");
});

showQuizBtn.addEventListener("click", () => {
  quizSection.classList.remove("hidden");
  notesSection.classList.add("hidden");
  showQuizBtn.classList.add("active");
  showNotesBtn.classList.remove("active");
});

topicSelect.addEventListener("change", () => {
  loadTopic(topicSelect.value);
});

difficultySelect.addEventListener("change", () => {
  currentDifficulty = difficultySelect.value;

  if (!currentDifficulty) {
    resetQuizView();
    return;
  }

  currentQuestions = [...currentTopic.quizData[currentDifficulty]];
  currentQuestionIndex = 0;
  currentScore = 0;
  updateScore();
  showCurrentQuestion();
});

submitBtn.addEventListener("click", () => {
  const selectedOption = document.querySelector('input[name="quizOption"]:checked');

  if (!selectedOption) {
    alert("Please choose an answer first.");
    return;
  }

  const currentQuestion = currentQuestions[currentQuestionIndex];
  const userAnswer = selectedOption.value;
  const isCorrect = userAnswer === currentQuestion.correctAnswer;

  resultBox.classList.remove("hidden");
  resultBox.classList.toggle("incorrect", !isCorrect);
  nextBtn.classList.remove("hidden");
  restartBtn.classList.remove("hidden");

  if (isCorrect) {
    resultMessage.textContent = "Correct.";
    currentScore += 1;
    updateScore();
  } else {
    resultMessage.textContent = "Not quite right.";
  }

  correctAnswerSpan.textContent = currentQuestion.correctAnswer;
  answerExplanationSpan.textContent = currentQuestion.explanation;

  submitBtn.disabled = true;
  Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('input[name="quizOption"]')).forEach(input => {
    input.disabled = true;
  });

  if (currentQuestionIndex === currentQuestions.length - 1) {
    nextBtn.textContent = "Finish Level";
  } else {
    nextBtn.textContent = "Next Question";
  }
});

nextBtn.addEventListener("click", () => {
  if (currentQuestionIndex < currentQuestions.length - 1) {
    currentQuestionIndex += 1;
    showCurrentQuestion();
  } else {
    questionText.textContent = "You finished this level.";
    optionsContainer.innerHTML = "";
    difficultyBadge.textContent = labelForDifficulty(currentDifficulty);
    quizPlaceholder.classList.add("hidden");
    quizArea.classList.remove("hidden");
    resultBox.classList.remove("hidden");
    resultBox.classList.remove("incorrect");
    resultMessage.textContent = `Final score: ${currentScore} / ${currentQuestions.length}`;
    correctAnswerSpan.textContent = "Level completed";
    answerExplanationSpan.textContent = "Choose another difficulty or switch topic to keep practicing.";
    nextBtn.classList.add("hidden");
    submitBtn.disabled = true;
  }
});

restartBtn.addEventListener("click", () => {
  if (!currentDifficulty) return;
  currentQuestions = [...currentTopic.quizData[currentDifficulty]];
  currentQuestionIndex = 0;
  currentScore = 0;
  updateScore();
  showCurrentQuestion();
});

fillTopicSelect();
loadTopic(topics[0].id);
